1
00:00:40,257 --> 00:00:43,036


3
00:00:47,030 --> 00:00:50,241
<i>Of fine
and admirable beginnings.</i>

4
00:00:51,634 --> 00:00:55,984
<i>Five years ago, we came to
make an Eden on these shores.</i>

5
00:00:56,004 --> 00:00:58,681
<i>And had things gone
as we hoped,</i>

6
00:00:58,707 --> 00:01:02,454
<i>I truly believe we would have
remained here happily,</i>

7
00:01:02,478 --> 00:01:05,950
<i>dying peacefully in old age.</i>

8
00:01:08,183 --> 00:01:10,598
<i>When Friedrich
and I left Germany,</i>

9
00:01:10,619 --> 00:01:14,696
<i>ours was a flight
to total solitude.</i>

10
00:01:14,723 --> 00:01:17,466
<i>At the time, neither of
us could have imagined...</i>

11
00:01:17,492 --> 00:01:21,910
<i>that others would intrude
upon our island paradise.</i>

12
00:01:21,928 --> 00:01:25,904
<i>Nor could we have foretold the
strange and sinister drama...</i>

13
00:01:25,933 --> 00:01:29,178
<i>that would be unleashed
upon us all,</i>

14
00:01:29,202 --> 00:01:32,881
<i>a drama
that over five short years...</i>

15
00:01:32,906 --> 00:01:35,822
<i>would leave our dream
in fragments...</i>

16
00:01:35,842 --> 00:01:40,956
<i>and send my dear companion,
Friedrich, to his grave.</i>

17
00:01:54,658 --> 00:01:57,141
[ Man ]
I find it very mysterious...

18
00:01:57,161 --> 00:02:00,407
how on a little island like that
all these people can disappear.

19
00:02:06,004 --> 00:02:07,542
[ Woman ]
You can't rule out the fact...

20
00:02:07,572 --> 00:02:09,951
that somebody actually took
the law into their own hands...

21
00:02:09,973 --> 00:02:13,219
because it was the only way to
bring sanity back to the island.

22
00:02:18,682 --> 00:02:23,259
[Man #2 ] That is the passion of the whole
thing is that it just never got solved.

23
00:02:23,285 --> 00:02:26,268
[ Woman ] Floreana is just one
mystery on top of another.

24
00:02:55,015 --> 00:02:57,794
[Speaking Spanish]

25
00:03:48,263 --> 00:03:50,142
<i>[ Train Approaching ]</i>

26
00:04:02,845 --> 00:04:05,418
<i>[ Man Reading] Patience,
as Nietzsche says,</i>

27
00:04:05,447 --> 00:04:07,759
<i>is the most difficult
of virtues.</i>

28
00:04:07,782 --> 00:04:12,759
<i>My decision to leave behind my
lucrative practice of medicine...</i>

29
00:04:12,787 --> 00:04:16,967
<i>and go into solitude
is not a rash inspiration.</i>

30
00:04:16,991 --> 00:04:20,965
<i>For 20 years, the idea has
been maturing in my mind.</i>

31
00:04:20,994 --> 00:04:25,606
<i>Now, at the age of 43,
my time has come.</i>

32
00:04:31,104 --> 00:04:35,988
<i>Organized society appears to me
as a huge impersonal monster,</i>

33
00:04:36,007 --> 00:04:40,961
<i>forging ever new chains with
which to shackle its members.</i>

34
00:04:40,979 --> 00:04:43,690
<i>Civilized man works only
for money,</i>

35
00:04:43,715 --> 00:04:48,931
<i>while the world chases madly after
the ephemeral and the valueless.</i>

36
00:04:51,221 --> 00:04:54,206
<i>Fortunately, in Dore,
I have found a woman...</i>

37
00:04:54,225 --> 00:04:57,697
<i>who fully embraces
my point of view.</i>

38
00:04:57,727 --> 00:05:00,712
<i>[ Reading As Dore] With all the
strength and obstinacy in me,</i>

39
00:05:00,731 --> 00:05:03,943
<i>I have defended myself
against preconceived notions...</i>

40
00:05:03,968 --> 00:05:05,779
<i>of bourgeois homemaking.</i>

41
00:05:06,771 --> 00:05:08,308
<i>The German woman
has been content...</i>

42
00:05:08,338 --> 00:05:11,788
<i>to model herself through
the ages as the hausfrau,</i>

43
00:05:11,809 --> 00:05:16,558
<i>her horizon bounded by the four
walls of a few stuffy rooms.</i>

44
00:05:16,580 --> 00:05:21,933
<i>The emptiness and frustration of such
an existence poisons the spirit.</i>

45
00:05:25,954 --> 00:05:29,666
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] Dore and I are
turning our backs on civilization.</i>

46
00:05:29,691 --> 00:05:32,903
<i>We have mapped out a plan
to permanently migrate...</i>

47
00:05:32,927 --> 00:05:37,210
<i>to an uninhabited spot
on the earth's surface--</i>

48
00:05:37,232 --> 00:05:39,645
<i>the Galépagos.</i>

49
00:05:39,666 --> 00:05:44,916
<i>The explorer William Beebe has declared
these islands to be "the world's end"...</i>

50
00:05:44,938 --> 00:05:50,894
<i>and it is this isolated archipelago
on which we have set our hopes.</i>

51
00:05:53,179 --> 00:05:56,425
<i>[ Reading As Dore] To the consternation
of all our friends and relatives,</i>

52
00:05:56,449 --> 00:06:01,027
<i>Friedrich has left his wife,
and I, my husband.</i>

53
00:06:01,053 --> 00:06:03,536
<i>Love, in the ordinary meaning
of the word,</i>

54
00:06:03,556 --> 00:06:07,507
<i>does not convey my feeling
for this man.</i>

55
00:06:07,526 --> 00:06:11,411
<i>Friedrich is my teacher
and my guide.</i>

56
00:06:11,431 --> 00:06:13,673
<i>Friedrich is my fate.</i>

57
00:06:15,534 --> 00:06:18,016
[ Man ] Because my
grandfather told it to me...

58
00:06:18,036 --> 00:06:21,716
and my father told it to me,

59
00:06:21,741 --> 00:06:24,917
I have to tell the truth.

60
00:06:31,014 --> 00:06:33,657
Friedrich was a genius.

61
00:06:33,684 --> 00:06:37,363
But he, without any doubt,
like all genius people,

62
00:06:37,388 --> 00:06:41,168
he had also his dark sides.

63
00:06:41,191 --> 00:06:44,698
He was influenced
by the philosophy of Nietzsche,

64
00:06:44,727 --> 00:06:47,768
that you only have yourself.

65
00:06:47,797 --> 00:06:53,309
He wanted to go away because he
didn't love the human being.

66
00:06:53,335 --> 00:06:56,216
Nietzsche didn't love
the human being.

67
00:06:56,237 --> 00:07:01,123
But he should have known also
what Goethe said,

68
00:07:01,142 --> 00:07:07,154
that you cannot leave the
civilization without being punished.

69
00:07:07,181 --> 00:07:08,993
You will be punished.

70
00:07:09,818 --> 00:07:11,696
If you go alone on an island,

71
00:07:11,719 --> 00:07:16,934
there can happen
terrible things.

72
00:07:16,956 --> 00:07:20,374
And though I think the--

73
00:07:20,395 --> 00:07:26,646
the Galépagos tragedy
was programmized,

74
00:07:26,666 --> 00:07:28,237
like a movie,

75
00:07:28,267 --> 00:07:31,878
from the beginning
to the tragic end.

76
00:07:40,013 --> 00:07:43,394
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
On July 4, 1929,</i>

77
00:07:43,415 --> 00:07:46,832
<i>Friedrich and I sailed
from Amsterdam,</i>

78
00:07:46,852 --> 00:07:52,102
<i>and we rejoiced as the world
disappeared behind us.</i>

79
00:07:52,124 --> 00:07:57,441
<i>A four-week journey across the open
seas brought us to Guayaquil, Ecuador,</i>

80
00:07:57,461 --> 00:08:01,277
<i>where we were forced to spend the
entire month of August waiting...</i>

81
00:08:01,298 --> 00:08:05,613
<i>for the only schooner that sailed
between the mainland and Galépagos.</i>

82
00:08:07,838 --> 00:08:12,986
<i>Then, at last, we were truly on
the way to our promised land.</i>

83
00:08:17,747 --> 00:08:23,168
<i>Seeking total isolation, we avoided
the island of San Cristobal,</i>

84
00:08:23,185 --> 00:08:26,898
<i>for it serves as an outpost
of the Ecuadorean government.</i>

85
00:08:28,923 --> 00:08:30,836
<i>Nor did we choose Santa Cruz,</i>

86
00:08:30,859 --> 00:08:36,508
whose <i>shores were already dotted with the
houses of a dozen or more European settlers.</i>

87
00:08:39,268 --> 00:08:44,414
<i>Instead, we sailed to the
uninhabited island of Floreana,</i>

88
00:08:44,437 --> 00:08:49,323
<i>where our nearest neighbors would
be more than 60 miles away.</i>

89
00:08:54,581 --> 00:08:58,395
<i>As I caught my first glimpse
of Floreana '5 rugged shore,</i>

90
00:08:58,416 --> 00:09:02,301
<i>not a shadow of fear or regret
clouded my certainty...</i>

91
00:09:02,321 --> 00:09:05,236
<i>in our decision to settle here.</i>

92
00:09:05,256 --> 00:09:08,798
<i>It was September 19, 1929,</i>

93
00:09:08,827 --> 00:09:11,936
<i>and we were alone at last.</i>

94
00:09:19,270 --> 00:09:21,513
[ Squawking ]

95
00:09:26,276 --> 00:09:28,588
[Chirping]

96
00:09:36,453 --> 00:09:40,336
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] The shore
was a dead and thorny waste.</i>

97
00:09:40,356 --> 00:09:43,568
<i>But an hour's walk inland
revealed to us...</i>

98
00:09:43,592 --> 00:09:47,042
<i>a leafy sea of greenness.</i>

99
00:09:47,062 --> 00:09:51,482
<i>In the center of this fertile
basin welled up a clear spring,</i>

100
00:09:51,501 --> 00:09:54,848
<i>to support a lush growth
of vegetable life.</i>

101
00:09:54,870 --> 00:09:59,516
<i>We had found the ideal spot
for our future home.</i>

102
00:10:00,543 --> 00:10:04,016
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

103
00:10:29,001 --> 00:10:32,042
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] Our immediate
concern is to tame this wiid jungle...</i>

104
00:10:32,071 --> 00:10:34,485
<i>and to make from it a garden.</i>

105
00:10:34,506 --> 00:10:37,718
<i>There we will plant the seeds
we've brought from Germany,</i>

106
00:10:37,742 --> 00:10:41,124
<i>which are so crucial
to our sustenance.</i>

107
00:10:41,145 --> 00:10:44,893
<i>Dore and I are both vegetarians.</i>

108
00:10:44,917 --> 00:10:48,765
<i>We do not eat meat
as a matter of principle.</i>

109
00:10:55,259 --> 00:10:58,573
<i>Although this work is the
hardest I have ever undertaken,</i>

110
00:10:58,596 --> 00:11:01,738
<i>I approach it
with the utmost joy...</i>

111
00:11:01,764 --> 00:11:06,309
<i>for it ls the fulfillment
of a dream.</i>

112
00:11:06,336 --> 00:11:08,442
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] Friedrich
'5 herculean achievements...</i>

113
00:11:08,470 --> 00:11:11,010
<i>rouse my ambition
to do likewise,</i>

114
00:11:11,040 --> 00:11:15,618
<i>but I find that
my efforts pale beside his.</i>

115
00:11:15,644 --> 00:11:18,456
<i>My weakness and infirmity
frustrate me.</i>

116
00:11:20,950 --> 00:11:22,931
<i>When I first met Friedrich,</i>

117
00:11:22,950 --> 00:11:25,627
<i>I had been diagnosed
with multiple sclerosis...</i>

118
00:11:25,653 --> 00:11:29,070
<i>and told
my illness was incurable.</i>

119
00:11:29,090 --> 00:11:31,596
<i>But Friedrich was not
like my other doctors.</i>

120
00:11:32,560 --> 00:11:34,096
<i>When he took over my care,</i>

121
00:11:34,127 --> 00:11:36,838
<i>he talked about
the power of thought...</i>

122
00:11:36,863 --> 00:11:39,472
<i>and told me that
I need not submit to illness...</i>

123
00:11:39,499 --> 00:11:44,317
<i>if I would learn to think in a
way that would make me well.</i>

124
00:11:44,338 --> 00:11:46,912
<i>That was all well and good
in Germany,</i>

125
00:11:46,941 --> 00:11:49,047
<i>but here on Floreana,</i>

126
00:11:49,075 --> 00:11:54,053
<i>sometimes I find myself literally
unable to go another step.</i>

127
00:11:55,748 --> 00:11:59,791
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] I must frequently
remind Dore that Nietzsche says,</i>

128
00:11:59,818 --> 00:12:01,925
<i>"To live is to suffer.</i>

129
00:12:01,954 --> 00:12:06,168
<i>To survive is to find some
meaning in the suffering.”</i>

130
00:12:06,191 --> 00:12:10,438
<i>We cannot expect
to find a paradise anywhere...</i>

131
00:12:10,462 --> 00:12:13,469
<i>unless we are willing
to create it.</i>

132
00:12:15,133 --> 00:12:17,944
<i>[ Reading As Dore] I pull myself
together and struggle on,</i>

133
00:12:17,968 --> 00:12:23,253
<i>resolving to let no trifle interfere with
the fulfillment of our great mission.</i>

134
00:13:00,290 --> 00:13:01,930
[Birds Squawking]

135
00:13:08,466 --> 00:13:10,344
[Insects Buzzing]

136
00:13:13,136 --> 00:13:17,748
I would have a very hard time
leaving family, friends,

137
00:13:17,774 --> 00:13:21,314
the place I grew up and all that
and just departing forever...

138
00:13:21,343 --> 00:13:24,794
to some godforsaken corner
of the world.

139
00:13:24,814 --> 00:13:26,385
Like my parents did.

140
00:13:30,486 --> 00:13:32,627
Why would people do that,
you know?

141
00:13:32,654 --> 00:13:36,605
To leave civilized world
and come out to a rock.

142
00:13:50,370 --> 00:13:52,410
[Chirping]

143
00:13:54,774 --> 00:13:57,690
[ Woman ] Well, you asked me what
brought us to the Galépagos.

144
00:13:58,912 --> 00:14:01,121
Our life had no meaning.

145
00:14:05,651 --> 00:14:07,861
We wanted to leave Europe.

146
00:14:07,887 --> 00:14:10,130
We wanted to leave Belgium.

147
00:14:11,525 --> 00:14:13,199
You know
how you live in a city.

148
00:14:13,226 --> 00:14:17,177
You have to be your rank and
your work, and you buy a car.

149
00:14:19,297 --> 00:14:21,005
And we didn't like that.

150
00:14:25,837 --> 00:14:29,287
It's a utopia.
It's a desire.

151
00:14:29,306 --> 00:14:32,449
It may be naive.
It may be, um,

152
00:14:33,210 --> 00:14:35,158
a dream.

153
00:14:35,179 --> 00:14:36,921
Probably it was a dream,

154
00:14:36,947 --> 00:14:39,624
but we made it very real.
[ Laughs]

155
00:14:47,322 --> 00:14:49,669
[ Barking ]

156
00:14:57,899 --> 00:15:02,375
[ Man ] As far as I understood, my father
said he went out to find paradise.

157
00:15:02,404 --> 00:15:04,511
To get away from
the glittering shit, he said.

158
00:15:04,539 --> 00:15:06,578
Get away from the world
and get away from Hitler.

159
00:15:06,608 --> 00:15:08,988
My father was very anti-Hitler.

160
00:15:10,111 --> 00:15:11,819
Hitler was coming to power.

161
00:15:11,845 --> 00:15:16,127
And my grandfather, he wanted
his boys out of Germany.

162
00:15:17,385 --> 00:15:20,961
He had read
about the Galapagos Islands.

163
00:15:20,988 --> 00:15:24,303
So he sold his little farm,
gave the boys the money,

164
00:15:24,325 --> 00:15:26,499
and they went
over the border to Denmark...

165
00:15:26,526 --> 00:15:29,306
and they bought this boat
and sailed away.

166
00:15:31,430 --> 00:15:34,209
My father was a real islander.

167
00:15:35,734 --> 00:15:40,745
He didn't want all this movement
towards, you know,civilization.

168
00:15:57,087 --> 00:16:01,598
[ Man ] My father, yeah, he
was very, very independent.

169
00:16:05,563 --> 00:16:07,908
She was a real pioneer type too,
obviously.

170
00:16:07,931 --> 00:16:12,716
I think it applies to most people
coming to a place like this.

171
00:16:12,737 --> 00:16:16,118
They--
They left everything behind.

172
00:16:19,808 --> 00:16:24,283
There is a certain winnowing
process, you might say,

173
00:16:24,312 --> 00:16:27,628
of people moving
to a place like this.

174
00:16:29,151 --> 00:16:33,000
Lots of times it's going to be
people that don't really fit in,

175
00:16:33,020 --> 00:16:37,440
don't find it easy
to be part of a regular society.

176
00:16:37,459 --> 00:16:39,634
Which is probably gonna
make it not as easy...

177
00:16:39,660 --> 00:16:42,507
for them to get along
with other people.

178
00:16:54,241 --> 00:16:57,417
<i>[ Reading As Dore] We've now
been here a year and a half,</i>

179
00:16:57,443 --> 00:17:01,986
<i>and Friedo has begun to assume the
appearance of a human habitation.</i>

180
00:17:02,013 --> 00:17:07,332
<i>Yet, though our aim was
to lead a life of contemplation,</i>

181
00:17:07,352 --> 00:17:12,466
<i>the ceaseless manual toll has dulled
the edges of our spiritual life.</i>

182
00:17:12,491 --> 00:17:18,447
<i>Our Eden is no place of rest,
as I had thought it would be.</i>

183
00:17:18,462 --> 00:17:22,313
<i>And neither is this Eden
a peaceful one.</i>

184
00:17:23,902 --> 00:17:28,320
<i>Friedrich is seemingly eternally
dissatisfied with everything I do...</i>

185
00:17:28,338 --> 00:17:34,090
<i>and at times the conflict between us
bursts out into something horrible.</i>

186
00:17:34,111 --> 00:17:39,087
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] I want to see Dore
as more than other frail and cowardly women.</i>

187
00:17:39,115 --> 00:17:42,896
<i>I cannot relax the sternness
of her education.</i>

188
00:17:42,919 --> 00:17:45,094
<i>For us,
there is only discipline.</i>

189
00:17:45,121 --> 00:17:47,798
<i>We must conquer by will.</i>

190
00:17:49,259 --> 00:17:52,402
[ Fritz ] The letters that
Friedrich wrote home--

191
00:17:52,429 --> 00:17:56,904
He never wrote in his letters
any nice thing about her.

192
00:17:56,933 --> 00:18:00,246
He was only describing
her disease.

193
00:18:01,402 --> 00:18:03,077
My father was shocked...

194
00:18:03,104 --> 00:18:06,782
because there was nothing
written of love.

195
00:18:06,807 --> 00:18:11,055
Even nothing about, uh--

196
00:18:12,079 --> 00:18:13,389
pity.

197
00:18:13,414 --> 00:18:14,826
Yes?

198
00:18:15,782 --> 00:18:17,319
Look, for Dore,

199
00:18:17,351 --> 00:18:19,833
Friedrich was something
like a god.

200
00:18:20,620 --> 00:18:24,333
But, Dore surely began...

201
00:18:24,358 --> 00:18:27,807
to have another image
of Friedrich.

202
00:18:29,628 --> 00:18:31,165
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
Friedrich does not see...</i>

203
00:18:31,196 --> 00:18:34,442
<i>that I need to be loved
and treated kindly.</i>

204
00:18:34,466 --> 00:18:39,443
<i>He spends each hard-earned minute of
spare time on his philosophical work...</i>

205
00:18:39,471 --> 00:18:42,615
<i>and is unconscious
of everything else.</i>

206
00:18:42,641 --> 00:18:45,351
<i>As solace,
I turn to my burro,</i>

207
00:18:45,377 --> 00:18:49,796
<i>lavishing on him all the care
and attention I have to give.</i>

208
00:18:49,814 --> 00:18:53,765
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] Dore '5
attachment to wiid creatures...</i>

209
00:18:53,784 --> 00:18:57,132
<i>is a source
of great disappointment to me.</i>

210
00:18:57,153 --> 00:19:02,199
<i>She thinks that her love of
animals is good and admirable,</i>

211
00:19:02,226 --> 00:19:04,264
<i>but her affection
for them is...</i>

212
00:19:04,294 --> 00:19:08,610
<i>nothing but a flattering
of the animal within herself.</i>

213
00:19:10,366 --> 00:19:13,248
<i>[ Reading As Dore] I confess that I
do spend a great deal of time...</i>

214
00:19:13,269 --> 00:19:15,477
<i>with my dear burro.</i>

215
00:19:15,504 --> 00:19:19,479
<i>Sometimes, however,
even he is not enough.</i>

216
00:19:19,508 --> 00:19:22,548
<i>Often I feel that
I should go mad with joy...</i>

217
00:19:22,576 --> 00:19:25,959
<i>if any other human being
should come into sight.</i>

218
00:19:25,980 --> 00:19:28,463
<i>Even a cannibal.</i>

219
00:19:28,483 --> 00:19:31,364
<i>Even a bloodthirsty buccaneer.</i>

220
00:19:45,933 --> 00:19:47,744
[ Woman ]
No school.

221
00:19:47,768 --> 00:19:49,442
No doctor.

222
00:19:50,638 --> 00:19:55,455
No stores.
No medicines to be bought.

223
00:19:56,576 --> 00:19:59,684
No communications hardly at all.

224
00:20:01,113 --> 00:20:03,026
If the world had gone under
out there,

225
00:20:03,049 --> 00:20:05,030
we wouldn't have known a thing.

226
00:20:05,717 --> 00:20:07,892
[ Blowing ]

227
00:20:10,755 --> 00:20:13,467
I'm Carmen Angermeyer
from Galépagos.

228
00:20:13,492 --> 00:20:15,632
I'm a housewife here.

229
00:20:15,660 --> 00:20:18,142
And I've lived here,
I think,

230
00:20:19,030 --> 00:20:22,343
74 years.

231
00:20:25,068 --> 00:20:28,849
My father was a very
practical person.

232
00:20:28,872 --> 00:20:30,911
And my father said--

233
00:20:30,941 --> 00:20:34,118
"There's going to be war,"
he said.

234
00:20:34,144 --> 00:20:36,215
"I can smell it,"
he said.

235
00:20:37,847 --> 00:20:41,059
He came out to the Galépagos
because he read some...

236
00:20:41,083 --> 00:20:45,935
of Dr. Ritter's articles
and stories.

237
00:20:45,954 --> 00:20:48,904
So he decided to have a look.

238
00:20:50,158 --> 00:20:52,002
He thought for him
it was very nice,

239
00:20:52,026 --> 00:20:56,605
but for women and children,
it was no good, he said.

240
00:20:56,632 --> 00:21:00,173
And my mother thought
that she might like it here.

241
00:21:00,202 --> 00:21:02,240
And so we came in '34.

242
00:21:04,306 --> 00:21:06,480
I was six.

243
00:21:07,709 --> 00:21:10,885
The only thing I didn't have
was playmates.

244
00:21:12,079 --> 00:21:14,492
That was about the only thing
that was missing.

245
00:21:18,984 --> 00:21:21,968
Occasionally a fish boat
would come.

246
00:21:24,756 --> 00:21:27,468
And of course the ship,
once in a while,

247
00:21:27,493 --> 00:21:31,069
went to take some cargo,
some foodstuff and so on.

248
00:21:32,664 --> 00:21:35,272
Mail,
which is so important.

249
00:21:35,299 --> 00:21:38,079
That made everybody furious--

250
00:21:38,103 --> 00:21:41,211
a ship came
and had forgotten the mail bag.

251
00:21:41,239 --> 00:21:42,878
And then you got
the letters later.

252
00:21:42,906 --> 00:21:46,379
They were almost a year old
the next time the ship came.

253
00:21:58,889 --> 00:22:01,531
<i>[ Reading As Dore] The cargo boat
put in at Post Office Bay...</i>

254
00:22:01,558 --> 00:22:03,905
<i>for the first time
in six months,</i>

255
00:22:03,927 --> 00:22:08,572
<i>bringing a parcel of mail from Germany,
as well as several newspapers.</i>

256
00:22:12,534 --> 00:22:18,046
<i>It seems that our letters home to
Germany have been leaked to the press.</i>

257
00:22:18,073 --> 00:22:22,754
<i>People in many countries have read
garbled and exaggerated accounts...</i>

258
00:22:22,778 --> 00:22:27,093
<i>of who we are and what our aims
have been in fleeing civilization.</i>

259
00:22:28,283 --> 00:22:31,095
<i>I feel as if the things
we hold most sacred...</i>

260
00:22:31,118 --> 00:22:34,000
<i>have been dragged mercilessly
through the mire...</i>

261
00:22:34,021 --> 00:22:36,561
<i>and that Friedrich and I
have been made to look...</i>

262
00:22:36,591 --> 00:22:41,044
<i>like a pair of eccentrics escaped
from some psychological</i> zoo.

263
00:22:50,903 --> 00:22:54,354
<i>[ Man Reading] Log entry.
January 3, 1932.</i>

264
00:22:54,373 --> 00:22:57,288
<i>Aboard the research vessel
Velero</i> III.

265
00:22:57,309 --> 00:22:58,346
[ Chattering ]

266
00:22:58,377 --> 00:23:00,324
<i>We are a crew
of 20 scientists...</i>

267
00:23:00,345 --> 00:23:03,158
<i>under the command
of Captain Allan Hancock,</i>

268
00:23:03,181 --> 00:23:07,758
<i>Los Angeles oilman, banker,
expert seaman, philanthropist...</i>

269
00:23:07,784 --> 00:23:10,530
<i>and patron of pure science.</i>

270
00:23:10,555 --> 00:23:13,971
<i>I am John Garth,
entomologist,</i>

271
00:23:13,991 --> 00:23:16,940
<i>known to my shipmates
as ”Bugs.”</i>

272
00:23:16,960 --> 00:23:19,500
<i>Our mission here
in the Galépagos...</i>

273
00:23:19,530 --> 00:23:23,505
<i>is to collect and document the
rarest of biological specimens.</i>

274
00:23:23,534 --> 00:23:28,648
<i>But today, we are stopping on the island
of Floreana for a very different reason--</i>

275
00:23:28,672 --> 00:23:33,250
<i>to visit the modern-day Adam and
Eve rumored to be living there.</i>

276
00:23:33,276 --> 00:23:35,953
<i>Accounts of this hermit couple
describe them...</i>

277
00:23:35,979 --> 00:23:40,125
<i>as nudists, cavemen,
eccentric philosophers.</i>

278
00:23:41,383 --> 00:23:44,493
<i>We</i> look <i>forward to meeting them
with much curiosity.</i>

279
00:23:49,157 --> 00:23:52,665
<i>We were shocked to find that,
contrary to all the lurid reports,</i>

280
00:23:52,694 --> 00:23:56,612
<i>the Rltters are actually one of the
most clever couples in the world.</i>

281
00:23:56,631 --> 00:23:59,011
<i>Dr. Ritter has devised
many tools and methods...</i>

282
00:23:59,033 --> 00:24:01,242
<i>to wrest what they can
out of this arid land.</i>

283
00:24:07,775 --> 00:24:10,951
<i>Many photographs
and moving pictures were taken.</i>

284
00:24:13,414 --> 00:24:16,590
<i>Indeed, when Dr. Ritter
demonstrated his new shower bath,</i>

285
00:24:16,616 --> 00:24:19,463
<i>at least six cameras
covered the event.</i>

286
00:24:21,653 --> 00:24:23,225
<i>Call them freaks,
if you like,</i>

287
00:24:23,255 --> 00:24:26,432
<i>but they have had the courage to
put their theories to the test...</i>

288
00:24:26,458 --> 00:24:28,407
<i>and make a practical experiment.</i>

289
00:24:29,796 --> 00:24:32,004
<i>We insisted they pay a visit
to the Velero,</i>

290
00:24:32,030 --> 00:24:34,639
<i>and despite their professed
dislike of human society,</i>

291
00:24:34,666 --> 00:24:37,478
<i>they eagerly took us up
on this invitation.</i>

292
00:24:42,273 --> 00:24:45,849
<i>We welcomed the Ritters aboard
with classics of German music.</i>

293
00:24:48,045 --> 00:24:50,323
<i>Dore was moved to tears
by our concert...</i>

294
00:24:50,347 --> 00:24:54,458
<i>and seemed more than a bit
nostalgic for her native land.</i>

295
00:24:54,484 --> 00:24:56,021
<i>The doctor,
on the other hand,</i>

296
00:24:56,052 --> 00:24:58,331
<i>looked uncomfortable
with her emotional display...</i>

297
00:24:58,355 --> 00:25:02,500
<i>and tried to distract her with a lecture
on the psychological unity of music.</i>

298
00:25:04,092 --> 00:25:05,937
<i>Before sending the Ritters back
to shore,</i>

299
00:25:05,961 --> 00:25:09,707
<i>Captain Hancock pressed them to tell
him of any provisions they lacked.</i>

300
00:25:09,731 --> 00:25:13,707
<i>Initially, Dr. Ritter would only admit
to needing lamp oil by which to write.</i>

301
00:25:13,736 --> 00:25:17,414
<i>But in the end, he also
accepted gifts of soap, rice,</i>

302
00:25:17,439 --> 00:25:19,821
<i>chocolate, cooking oil,
a stove...</i>

303
00:25:19,843 --> 00:25:22,826
<i>and even a Winchester rifle.</i>

304
00:25:22,845 --> 00:25:25,122
<i>For all their claims
of self-sufficiency,</i>

305
00:25:25,146 --> 00:25:29,566
<i>they both seemed quite glad as they
left the ship, laden with this bounty.</i>

306
00:25:32,353 --> 00:25:35,338
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] As the Velero
crew took us back to Floreana,</i>

307
00:25:35,357 --> 00:25:37,804
<i>I thought wistfully
of the lovely music...</i>

308
00:25:37,824 --> 00:25:41,207
<i>that we should
probably never hear again...</i>

309
00:25:41,228 --> 00:25:47,080
<i>and of the sympathetic new friends
who were leaving us all too soon.</i>

310
00:25:47,099 --> 00:25:49,913
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] The visit by
Captain Hancock and his scientists...</i>

311
00:25:49,937 --> 00:25:52,010
<i>was well and good.</i>

312
00:25:52,038 --> 00:25:54,748
<i>They are like-minded people.</i>

313
00:25:54,774 --> 00:25:58,314
<i>But should others turn up intending
to disrupt our solitude...</i>

314
00:25:58,342 --> 00:26:00,450
<i>in a more permanent fashion,</i>

315
00:26:00,480 --> 00:26:03,827
<i>we will not be so hospitable.</i>

316
00:26:03,848 --> 00:26:08,858
<i>We shall resolutely resist the
establishment of any community.</i>

317
00:26:19,163 --> 00:26:21,474
[Jacqueline] We certainly didn't
come with the same attraction...

318
00:26:21,498 --> 00:26:25,108
that nowadays the thousands
of visitors that come here.

319
00:26:26,503 --> 00:26:28,712
That was not why we came here.

320
00:26:30,940 --> 00:26:33,115
When we came here
in the Galépagos,

321
00:26:33,877 --> 00:26:35,754
we were on our OVVFI.

322
00:26:39,548 --> 00:26:42,190
It was just rocks
and a few houses.

323
00:26:45,154 --> 00:26:47,659
We could take land
what we wanted.

324
00:26:47,690 --> 00:26:51,504
People told us that, um, people
who come here and want to have...

325
00:26:51,525 --> 00:26:54,408
a piece of land,
it's about 200 hectares.

326
00:26:55,831 --> 00:26:57,572
Free.
Just take it.

327
00:27:12,646 --> 00:27:15,288
[ Man ] What I always felt
from Mom and Dad was...

328
00:27:15,314 --> 00:27:19,733
they wanted a place
that was primitive enough...

329
00:27:19,752 --> 00:27:24,330
to not have people tell you
what to do or what to not do.

330
00:27:26,524 --> 00:27:28,939
To find that kind
of paradise,

331
00:27:28,960 --> 00:27:31,911
you have to look for a place
you never hear of.

332
00:27:31,930 --> 00:27:33,468
Because if you hear
about it--

333
00:27:33,499 --> 00:27:35,844
It doesn't exist. It's
obviously out to the world...

334
00:27:35,867 --> 00:27:39,546
and it's bound to be sentenced
to not be a paradise anymore.

335
00:27:41,504 --> 00:27:43,613
[Jacqueline] I don't like to
use that word "paradise."

336
00:27:43,642 --> 00:27:45,679
Why the people
are always using that--

337
00:27:45,708 --> 00:27:47,349
Well, you were looking for-- No.

338
00:27:47,378 --> 00:27:49,382
We were not looking
for a paradise. Please.

339
00:27:49,413 --> 00:27:52,863
No, not a paradise, but-- We
were looking for a place...

340
00:27:52,883 --> 00:27:57,199
where we were our own masters
and that it depends on ourself.

341
00:27:57,220 --> 00:27:59,759
[ Gil ] And that's
exactly what you found.

342
00:28:01,724 --> 00:28:05,733
Well, I don't know. If there is a
paradise, I hope it's nicer than this.

343
00:28:06,729 --> 00:28:08,676
[Birds Singing]

344
00:28:08,697 --> 00:28:10,873
[Bird Calling]

345
00:28:28,148 --> 00:28:30,757
[Chirping]

346
00:28:33,986 --> 00:28:36,128
[Chirping Continues]

347
00:28:38,659 --> 00:28:40,765
[ Squawking ]

348
00:28:57,410 --> 00:28:59,357
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
I do not know why it is...</i>

349
00:28:59,377 --> 00:29:03,990
<i>that certain events cast ominous
shadows long before they come about.</i>

350
00:29:04,016 --> 00:29:08,196
<i>But so it was with me
before the Wittmers came.</i>

351
00:29:08,219 --> 00:29:12,136
<i>The weather was perfect.
The garden growing well.</i>

352
00:29:12,156 --> 00:29:17,839
<i>And yet, something within me
refused to be quieted.</i>

353
00:29:17,861 --> 00:29:22,371
<i>Then, one morning, far out
at sea, we saw a schooner,</i>

354
00:29:22,398 --> 00:29:25,872
<i>which seemed
to be approaching Black Beach.</i>

355
00:29:32,107 --> 00:29:35,923
<i>[Woman Reading] I felt terribly
alone that day in August 1932...</i>

356
00:29:35,945 --> 00:29:39,726
<i>when we first landed
on Floreana.</i>

357
00:29:39,748 --> 00:29:44,963
<i>Surely no more forlorn and forbidding
place could be imagined than this island.</i>

358
00:29:45,988 --> 00:29:49,461
<i>My husband, Heinz,
and I did not speak.</i>

359
00:29:49,491 --> 00:29:51,631
<i>We felt too downhearted.</i>

360
00:29:51,659 --> 00:29:53,869
<i>Yet,
there was no going back.</i>

361
00:29:53,895 --> 00:29:57,505
<i>We had invested all our savings
on equipment and supplies...</i>

362
00:29:57,531 --> 00:30:01,039
<i>and in so doing
had burnt our bridges.</i>

363
00:30:01,068 --> 00:30:04,109
<i>It might be months
before another ship put in here.</i>

364
00:30:04,138 --> 00:30:05,981
<i>And even if a ship did come,</i>

365
00:30:06,005 --> 00:30:10,959
<i>we could hardly get back to Germany on
the 20 marks we had left between us.</i>

366
00:30:15,148 --> 00:30:19,032
<i>[ Man Reading] I must admit that
this landscape is not encouraging.</i>

367
00:30:19,052 --> 00:30:21,693
<i>It is certainly
no South Sea paradise,</i>

368
00:30:21,720 --> 00:30:26,070
<i>and the weight of the decision to come
here rests heavy on my shoulders.</i>

369
00:30:26,090 --> 00:30:30,134
<i>My son, Harry, from my first marriage,
has always been delicate...</i>

370
00:30:30,162 --> 00:30:34,239
<i>and last spring his health
took a turn for the worse.</i>

371
00:30:34,266 --> 00:30:39,743
<i>It was then that I came across Friedrich
Ritter's articles in the Cologne newspapers.</i>

372
00:30:39,770 --> 00:30:44,986
<i>While reading his words, I realized
that the Galépagos is our solution.</i>

373
00:30:45,009 --> 00:30:48,015
<i>If the Ritters could do it,
so could we.</i>

374
00:30:48,045 --> 00:30:50,287
<i>We too can leave city life
behind us...</i>

375
00:30:50,312 --> 00:30:54,696
<i>and give Harry a healthy</i>
Swiss <i>Family Robinson existence.</i>

376
00:30:57,153 --> 00:30:59,864
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] I confess
that I was sadly disappointed...</i>

377
00:30:59,889 --> 00:31:02,462
<i>at our first meeting
with the Wittmers.</i>

378
00:31:02,491 --> 00:31:07,503
<i>Frau Wittmer in particular looks to
be a rather ordinary type of woman...</i>

379
00:31:07,530 --> 00:31:11,639
<i>who would like nothing more than
to devote herself to housekeeping.</i>

380
00:31:11,666 --> 00:31:15,675
<i>It is clear that neither of the
newcomers share our spiritual goals,</i>

381
00:31:15,703 --> 00:31:20,747
<i>and I am quite certain that life in the
wilderness will soon lose its charm for them.</i>

382
00:31:22,342 --> 00:31:23,879
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
Upon our arrival,</i>

383
00:31:23,910 --> 00:31:27,794
<i>Dore immediately began discussing
the philosophy of Nietzsche.</i>

384
00:31:27,814 --> 00:31:30,093
<i>I found this a bit absurd.</i>

385
00:31:30,117 --> 00:31:33,158
<i>We want to be settlers
in a more ordinary sense.</i>

386
00:31:33,187 --> 00:31:38,072
<i>Our equipment is not Nietzsche, but
perseverance and the will to work.</i>

387
00:31:38,091 --> 00:31:42,544
<i>We felt rather out of place
and prepared to leave.</i>

388
00:31:42,562 --> 00:31:46,173
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] They came expecting
to be treated like invited guests,</i>

389
00:31:46,199 --> 00:31:48,272
<i>and the only way
we can deal with them...</i>

390
00:31:48,301 --> 00:31:53,812
<i>is to make it clear from the beginning
that we consider them intruders.</i>

391
00:31:53,838 --> 00:31:56,048
<i>Wanting them
as far from us as possible,</i>

392
00:31:56,074 --> 00:32:00,219
<i>I took them more than an hour's
difficult journey up the hiH...</i>

393
00:32:00,244 --> 00:32:05,962
<i>and showed them some old pirate
caves with a nearby spring.</i>

394
00:32:08,019 --> 00:32:09,693
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
There were the caves.</i>

395
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:13,466
<i>Three of them together
under the slope of a hiH.</i>

396
00:32:13,489 --> 00:32:18,740
<i>I immediately began sweeping the interior of
the largest, which would be our new home.</i>

397
00:32:18,761 --> 00:32:21,439
<i>How glad we are
that these caves exist.</i>

398
00:32:21,465 --> 00:32:26,008
<i>And yet it concerns us that we are
now located so far from Dr. Ritter.</i>

399
00:32:27,504 --> 00:32:31,284
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

400
00:32:53,261 --> 00:32:55,105
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ]
I find it shocking...</i>

401
00:32:55,128 --> 00:33:00,173
<i>that the Wittmers have come to Floreana to
take advantage of my skill as a physician.</i>

402
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:04,914
<i>I have made it eminently clear that I do
not intend to practice as a doctor...</i>

403
00:33:04,937 --> 00:33:10,051
<i>and that I refuse to sit around the
caves all day attending to Margret.</i>

404
00:33:10,076 --> 00:33:12,524
<i>I am highly resentful...</i>

405
00:33:12,544 --> 00:33:17,521
<i>and would gladly put all of them on
the next boat back to Guayaquil.</i>

406
00:33:17,549 --> 00:33:22,526
<i>[ Reading As Heinz] Ritter's unwillingness
to assist us is a great disappointment.</i>

407
00:33:22,554 --> 00:33:25,662
<i>It seems a pity
that he should be so unpleasant,</i>

408
00:33:25,690 --> 00:33:29,266
<i>especially as we happen
to all be Germans.</i>

409
00:33:29,293 --> 00:33:35,250
<i>[ Reading As Margret] I wonder if Dr. Ritter
really grasps that if something goes wrong,</i>

410
00:33:35,265 --> 00:33:40,185
<i>he will carry a heavy burden of
responsibility for refusing to give me help.</i>

411
00:33:40,204 --> 00:33:44,087
<i>What kind of doctor
could be so heartless?</i>

412
00:33:45,876 --> 00:33:48,324
[Train Approaching]

413
00:33:51,814 --> 00:33:53,591
[Whistle Blows]

414
00:34:06,360 --> 00:34:09,777
<i>N</i> [ Clarinet]

415
00:34:40,359 --> 00:34:42,774
[ Fritz] Dr. Ritter
came out of a family...

416
00:34:42,795 --> 00:34:47,578
for which the emperor
and the fatherland...

417
00:34:47,599 --> 00:34:50,844
were the most important thing.

418
00:34:50,868 --> 00:34:54,150
So, when
the First World War began,

419
00:34:54,173 --> 00:34:59,183
it was naturally
that he and also my father...

420
00:34:59,210 --> 00:35:03,561
go to war
to defend the fatherland.

421
00:35:04,581 --> 00:35:07,965
They went with flowers
on their rifles,

422
00:35:07,986 --> 00:35:09,796
singing, drinking beer,

423
00:35:09,820 --> 00:35:13,532
thinking that this war
will be finished in six weeks.

424
00:35:15,759 --> 00:35:20,338
But they ended
in these frontline trenches,

425
00:35:20,364 --> 00:35:26,116
seeing the dead and wounded
people everywhere around.

426
00:35:26,136 --> 00:35:31,715
Then they begin to understand
what really war is.

427
00:35:33,442 --> 00:35:36,118
And, in his philosophy,

428
00:35:36,144 --> 00:35:41,259
Friedrich said
that war is fixed...

429
00:35:41,284 --> 00:35:44,324
in the genes
of the human being.

430
00:35:45,085 --> 00:35:47,399
It is fixed in the genes,

431
00:35:48,522 --> 00:35:50,629
the character of human being.

432
00:35:54,661 --> 00:35:58,806
Surely, he was scarred
by the First World War.

433
00:35:58,831 --> 00:36:03,911
And I think
that this changed him a lot.

434
00:36:28,393 --> 00:36:31,604
[Insects Buzzing]

435
00:36:31,628 --> 00:36:34,635
[ Steve] "There's a race
of men that don't fit in,

436
00:36:34,665 --> 00:36:37,341
a race that can't stay still.

437
00:36:37,367 --> 00:36:40,250
So they break the hearts
of kith and kin...

438
00:36:40,271 --> 00:36:42,843
and they roam the world
at will.

439
00:36:44,240 --> 00:36:47,122
They range the field
and they rove the flood...

440
00:36:47,143 --> 00:36:50,025
and they climb
the mountain's crest.

441
00:36:50,046 --> 00:36:52,756
Theirs is the curse
of the gypsy blood,

442
00:36:52,781 --> 00:36:55,856
and they don't know
how to rest.

443
00:36:55,884 --> 00:36:59,096
They say,
'Could I find my proper groove,

444
00:36:59,120 --> 00:37:02,264
what a deep mark
I would make.'

445
00:37:02,291 --> 00:37:05,902
So they chop and change
and each fresh move...

446
00:37:05,928 --> 00:37:08,273
is only a fresh mistake."

447
00:37:10,831 --> 00:37:12,780
"The Men That Don't Fit In."

448
00:37:13,933 --> 00:37:16,713
That was one
of my father's favorite poems.

449
00:37:17,805 --> 00:37:19,342
Robert Service.

450
00:37:24,079 --> 00:37:26,389
[ Barks]

451
00:37:26,412 --> 00:37:28,793
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Today was
a day of great excitement.</i>

452
00:37:28,815 --> 00:37:31,492
<i>Our first visitors have come.</i>

453
00:37:31,518 --> 00:37:33,430
<i>This morning
I heard our dog barking...</i>

454
00:37:33,452 --> 00:37:37,267
<i>and through the trees, I saw a
small, slim woman of about 40...</i>

455
00:37:37,289 --> 00:37:40,273
<i>riding up on a donkey
and carrying a revolver.</i>

456
00:37:41,626 --> 00:37:43,506
<i>There were two German men
with her,</i>

457
00:37:43,529 --> 00:37:47,411
<i>one thin and blond
and the other dark and swarthy.</i>

458
00:37:47,431 --> 00:37:51,976
<i>Both of them appear to be
gentlemen-in-waiting, or perhaps even lovers.</i>

459
00:37:52,003 --> 00:37:55,476
<i>What an extraordinary trio.</i>

460
00:37:55,506 --> 00:37:57,216
<i>As the woman dismounted,</i>

461
00:37:57,242 --> 00:38:02,661
<i>she introduced herself as Baroness von
Wagner from Paris, by way of Vienna,</i>

462
00:38:02,678 --> 00:38:06,529
<i>and proceeded to make an announcement
that was more than a little alarming.</i>

463
00:38:07,951 --> 00:38:11,664
<i>[Woman Reading] Darlings, you
know my plans, don't you?</i>

464
00:38:11,688 --> 00:38:14,432
<i>I've come
to establish a grand hotel.</i>

465
00:38:14,457 --> 00:38:17,270
<i>It will be called
Hacienda Paradiso.</i>

466
00:38:18,561 --> 00:38:23,538
<i>Philippson is my architect
and Lorenz my engineer.</i>

467
00:38:23,566 --> 00:38:26,139
<i>After long and mature analysis,</i>

468
00:38:26,168 --> 00:38:31,885
<i>I've come to the conclusion
that my project is feasible.</i>

469
00:38:31,906 --> 00:38:35,880
<i>After all,
woman is capable of everything,</i>

470
00:38:35,909 --> 00:38:39,861
<i>from the highest
to the lowest.</i>

471
00:38:39,880 --> 00:38:45,838
<i>Certainly she is greater
and more resolved than the male.</i>

472
00:38:50,491 --> 00:38:53,407
<i>[ Reading As Heinz] What a strange
figure the baroness presents.</i>

473
00:38:53,427 --> 00:38:56,899
<i>I think she might have dreams
of being a feudal queen,</i>

474
00:38:56,929 --> 00:39:01,541
<i>with servants, retainers and slaves
to carry out her slightest wish.</i>

475
00:39:01,567 --> 00:39:04,608
<i>Margret and I gazed
at her speechless...</i>

476
00:39:04,636 --> 00:39:10,422
<i>as she announced that she and her men
would be living in our orange grove,</i>

477
00:39:10,442 --> 00:39:13,550
<i>beside our little stream.</i>

478
00:39:13,577 --> 00:39:19,727
<i>She said she wouldn't dream of living
anywhere else until her hotel is built.</i>

479
00:39:20,819 --> 00:39:22,425
<i>We've hardly been here
two months,</i>

480
00:39:22,454 --> 00:39:26,735
<i>and already there are unwelcome neighbors
living right outside our door.</i>

481
00:39:28,926 --> 00:39:31,238
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Foregoing
any of the normal courtesies,</i>

482
00:39:31,261 --> 00:39:34,403
<i>the baroness
marched over to our spring.</i>

483
00:39:34,430 --> 00:39:36,674
<i>She was followed closely
by the blond,</i>

484
00:39:36,700 --> 00:39:39,706
<i>who took off her shoes
like a devoted servant...</i>

485
00:39:39,735 --> 00:39:45,054
<i>and proceeded to wash her feet
thoroughly in our drinking water.</i>

486
00:39:45,074 --> 00:39:48,251
<i>After this ceremony
had been completed,</i>

487
00:39:48,277 --> 00:39:51,956
<i>the baroness took her leave to pay
her first visit to the Ritters.</i>

488
00:39:53,716 --> 00:39:56,198
<i>[ Reading As Dore] Without
waiting for an invitation,</i>

489
00:39:56,218 --> 00:39:59,031
<i>she settled
in one of our deck chairs.</i>

490
00:39:59,054 --> 00:40:01,935
<i>She then demanded a cup of tea
with an attitude...</i>

491
00:40:01,956 --> 00:40:07,377
<i>that made it clear she regarded
Friedo more or less as hers.</i>

492
00:40:07,394 --> 00:40:09,536
<i>The baroness told us
of her plan...</i>

493
00:40:09,564 --> 00:40:14,951
<i>to turn Floreana into a kind of
Miami for American millionaires.</i>

494
00:40:14,969 --> 00:40:18,441
<i>We are appalled
at this profit-making scheme.</i>

495
00:40:18,471 --> 00:40:25,556
<i>The very idea of it casts a
sordid blight upon our island.</i>

496
00:40:25,579 --> 00:40:29,428
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] I, for one,
am disgusted by her theatricals.</i>

497
00:40:29,449 --> 00:40:34,961
<i>If she had a single proper man with her,
instead of a pair of servile gigolos,</i>

498
00:40:34,987 --> 00:40:38,334
<i>she could be kept in order
without trouble.</i>

499
00:40:38,355 --> 00:40:43,936
<i>As you can imagine, we weren't too pleased
to have her giving orders in our house,</i>

500
00:40:43,963 --> 00:40:48,073
<i>and Dore told her so
in no uncertain terms.</i>

501
00:40:48,099 --> 00:40:51,482
<i>In the end, the baroness
went off highly offended,</i>

502
00:40:51,503 --> 00:40:54,418
<i>breathing fire and slaughter
against us.</i>

503
00:40:58,543 --> 00:41:02,221
<i>[ Reading As Dore] She is in one
way so trivial and frivolous...</i>

504
00:41:02,246 --> 00:41:05,718
<i>and in another way
so sinister.</i>

505
00:41:05,748 --> 00:41:11,669
<i>But unlike Margret Wittmer, at least the
baroness ls no little bourgeois hausfrau.</i>

506
00:41:11,687 --> 00:41:16,767
<i>Even as an enemy, she is a
person worthy of one's steel.</i>

507
00:41:19,862 --> 00:41:23,210
[ Man, Heavy Accent]

508
00:42:38,269 --> 00:42:39,840
<i>[ Gunshot]</i>

509
00:42:43,438 --> 00:42:45,888
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Today we
had a tremendous commotion.</i>

510
00:42:45,909 --> 00:42:51,124
<i>Two Norwegians who live on Santa Cruz
Island dropped anchor in Post Office Bay.</i>

511
00:42:51,146 --> 00:42:55,064
<i>One of them, Christian Stampa,
shot a small calf,</i>

512
00:42:55,084 --> 00:42:57,622
<i>intending to return with it
to Santa Cruz.</i>

513
00:42:57,651 --> 00:43:01,627
<i>Upon hearing the shot,
the baroness charged out.</i>

514
00:43:20,272 --> 00:43:24,281
<i>[ Reading As Margret ] "That was my
calf," she shouted. "Philippson! "</i>

515
00:43:24,310 --> 00:43:28,127
<i>And Philippson came out,
taking up a stand near her.</i>

516
00:43:28,148 --> 00:43:30,390
<i>Both men yielded and fled.</i>

517
00:43:38,189 --> 00:43:40,263
<i>[ Reading As Dore] We were
awakened by frantic shouts,</i>

518
00:43:40,292 --> 00:43:44,676
<i>and to my horror I saw Christian
Stampa staggering towards our house.</i>

519
00:43:44,696 --> 00:43:49,911
<i>His clothes were torn to ribbons and
his face was white and set like iron.</i>

520
00:43:49,934 --> 00:43:54,854
<i>Apparently the baroness had confronted
him with violent gestures and a rifle,</i>

521
00:43:54,872 --> 00:43:57,946
<i>yelling that the island is now
hers, with everything upon it.</i>

522
00:43:59,109 --> 00:44:02,524
<i>This story has shattered
even Friedrich '5 calm.</i>

523
00:44:02,545 --> 00:44:07,363
<i>He has written up a detailed report about
the baroness's fantastic behavior.</i>

524
00:44:07,383 --> 00:44:12,770
<i>Stampa is taking this report to
the governor on San Cristobal.</i>

525
00:44:22,198 --> 00:44:24,805
[Chirping]

526
00:44:34,040 --> 00:44:37,891
[ Man ] You take 100,000 people and 1,000
people-- island life is exactly the same.

527
00:44:39,181 --> 00:44:42,790
The same sort of mechanics
as to society are happening.

528
00:44:46,586 --> 00:44:49,331
My name is
Daniel Fitter Angermeyer.

529
00:44:51,392 --> 00:44:54,399
I suppose
I'm third-generation Angermeyer.

530
00:44:56,195 --> 00:44:58,405
I was born here in Galépagos.

531
00:45:00,299 --> 00:45:02,805
Small island environments,
you always had confrontations...

532
00:45:02,835 --> 00:45:05,785
and, you know,
problems going on for years.

533
00:45:05,805 --> 00:45:09,311
"So-and-so did that to me years ago, and
so-and-so did this to me years ago,

534
00:45:09,340 --> 00:45:11,720
and you never paid me
back that." I mean--

535
00:45:11,742 --> 00:45:13,417
Small island life.

536
00:45:18,015 --> 00:45:21,900
Like the saying goes, "Little
town, big hell," basically.

537
00:45:21,919 --> 00:45:24,457
Well, it was part
of that factor here too.

538
00:45:24,487 --> 00:45:29,669
So the people who paid, perhaps, a bit
too much attention on that factor,

539
00:45:29,692 --> 00:45:31,367
really got--
hit them hard.

540
00:45:31,394 --> 00:45:33,899
There was nowhere to escape.

541
00:45:33,930 --> 00:45:38,680
The people were very friendly,
but distant, and so on.

542
00:45:38,701 --> 00:45:44,017
We talked about many things,
but each of us in your house.

543
00:45:44,038 --> 00:45:49,426
And the leitmotif was, "We did it, we had
a hard time, and you have to learn."

544
00:45:50,978 --> 00:45:54,157
[Carmen] People had to
get going on their own.

545
00:45:54,183 --> 00:45:57,530
They could ask, everybody would
help them out.

546
00:45:57,552 --> 00:46:01,470
But everybody expected also that the
persons would make an effort, you know,

547
00:46:01,489 --> 00:46:03,026
and learn and go at it,

548
00:46:03,057 --> 00:46:07,772
and not just sit there and ask and
expect somebody doing it for them.

549
00:46:07,795 --> 00:46:11,678
I don't know.
I cannot give a name to that.

550
00:46:11,698 --> 00:46:13,475
Everyone for himself.

551
00:46:28,146 --> 00:46:31,290
<i>[ Reading As Margret] The first
labor pains began on December 30.</i>

552
00:46:31,317 --> 00:46:35,895
<i>"Dear God," I prayed,
"let it all go well. "</i>

553
00:46:35,921 --> 00:46:39,336
<i>Heinz wanted to send for Dr.
Ritter but I refused to let him,</i>

554
00:46:39,356 --> 00:46:43,706
<i>determined that we'd get along
somehow without his help.</i>

555
00:46:43,727 --> 00:46:49,183
<i>The pains were very violent, but the
day passed and so did the night.</i>

556
00:46:49,200 --> 00:46:53,050
<i>I got up, walked around a bit
and baked a New Year's cake...</i>

557
00:46:53,070 --> 00:46:56,144
<i>before the pains became too
agonizing for me to do anything...</i>

558
00:46:56,172 --> 00:46:59,349
<i>but lay and bite hard
into my pillows.</i>

559
00:47:00,844 --> 00:47:04,488
<i>That night passed too,
and now it was New Year's Day.</i>

560
00:47:04,513 --> 00:47:07,555
<i>It was 72 hours since
the pains had started,</i>

561
00:47:07,584 --> 00:47:11,056
<i>and they were more than
flesh and blood could stand.</i>

562
00:47:11,086 --> 00:47:14,833
<i>For a moment,
everything went black.</i>

563
00:47:14,858 --> 00:47:20,141
<i>I screamed so loud for Heinz that my own
voice echoed back through the cave.</i>

564
00:47:20,162 --> 00:47:22,370
<i>I could see one thing
quite clearly.</i>

565
00:47:22,396 --> 00:47:26,177
<i>My life was in danger
and only a doctor could save me.</i>

566
00:47:26,200 --> 00:47:29,913
<i>"Dr. Ritter," I muttered.
"Get Dr. Ritter."</i>

567
00:47:32,906 --> 00:47:37,290
<i>Three long hours passed before
Heinz returned with Dr. Ritter.</i>

568
00:47:37,310 --> 00:47:41,695
<i>Ritter examined me and was now
a doctor, pure and simple.</i>

569
00:47:41,715 --> 00:47:45,189
<i>He washed his hands a dozen
times with antiseptic soap,</i>

570
00:47:45,219 --> 00:47:48,099
<i>and then he performed
the operation.</i>

571
00:47:48,121 --> 00:47:51,594
<i>The pain was so cruel, I could
have screamed my head off.</i>

572
00:47:51,624 --> 00:47:54,938
<i>But somehow,
I managed to bear it in silence.</i>

573
00:47:58,429 --> 00:48:00,742
<i>Then suddenly, I heard a cry.</i>

574
00:48:00,766 --> 00:48:02,873
<i>A short, shrill cry.</i>

575
00:48:02,901 --> 00:48:06,181
<i>It was the first cry
of our newborn child.</i>

576
00:48:06,204 --> 00:48:11,454
<i>Dr. Ritter proceeded to congratulate
me on my baby son, Rolf.</i>

577
00:48:11,476 --> 00:48:13,355
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ]
Margret was very brave...</i>

578
00:48:13,378 --> 00:48:17,125
<i>and Rolf is certainly
a fine, strapping boy.</i>

579
00:48:17,148 --> 00:48:20,757
<i>I hope his upbringing
will be stern enough...</i>

580
00:48:20,784 --> 00:48:23,427
<i>to make of him
a worthwhile character.</i>

581
00:48:26,923 --> 00:48:28,598
<i>[ Reading As Margret ]
Shortly after Rolf's birth,</i>

582
00:48:28,625 --> 00:48:32,634
<i>the baroness came to visit
with Philippson and Lorenz.</i>

583
00:48:32,662 --> 00:48:38,208
<i>She had no revolver in her belt that day
and seemed in an unusually genial mood.</i>

584
00:48:38,234 --> 00:48:40,443
<i>After congratulating me
on my son,</i>

585
00:48:40,469 --> 00:48:44,046
<i>she presented me with clothes she
brought from her Paris boutique,</i>

586
00:48:44,073 --> 00:48:49,322
<i>announcing that he must be the "most
dapper little man on our island."</i>

587
00:48:49,344 --> 00:48:52,384
<i>♪ O Tannenbaum A'</i>

588
00:48:52,413 --> 00:48:53,951
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
The coming of the baby...</i>

589
00:48:53,981 --> 00:48:57,522
<i>created an atmosphere
almost like Christmas.</i>

590
00:48:57,551 --> 00:49:00,364
<i>Friedrich and I chose presents
for him--</i>

591
00:49:00,387 --> 00:49:03,963
<i>a two-year-old date palm,
vegetables, fruits.</i>

592
00:49:03,990 --> 00:49:07,237
<i>For the baroness,
we gave kitchen herbs.</i>

593
00:49:07,261 --> 00:49:11,075
<i>All differences and quarrels
were momentarily lost...</i>

594
00:49:11,096 --> 00:49:13,978
<i>in a general warmth
and goodwill,</i>

595
00:49:14,000 --> 00:49:17,850
<i>and I wanted very much that
we should all, from now on,</i>

596
00:49:17,870 --> 00:49:21,014
<i>live in harmony
and avoid future conflicts.</i>

597
00:49:21,041 --> 00:49:24,024
<i>s: [ Ends]</i>

598
00:49:44,763 --> 00:49:47,506
[Man Speaking Spanish]

599
00:51:16,480 --> 00:51:21,194
[ Woman ] I was the first European
girl born up in the highlands.

600
00:51:21,217 --> 00:51:23,165
And I was a surprise.

601
00:51:23,186 --> 00:51:25,259
Mom didn't know
I was on my way.

602
00:51:27,090 --> 00:51:31,041
But then,
she celebrated her birthday...

603
00:51:31,060 --> 00:51:34,272
and they all had potato salad.

604
00:51:34,296 --> 00:51:37,611
And in the evening,
in the night,

605
00:51:37,633 --> 00:51:41,346
she got a tummy ache
and she didn't feel well at all.

606
00:51:41,371 --> 00:51:44,877
And she said,
"It must be the potato salad."

607
00:51:44,906 --> 00:51:46,443
But it wasn't.

608
00:51:46,474 --> 00:51:49,048
It was me who was coming.

609
00:51:51,813 --> 00:51:54,294
I have some
very good memories, yes.

610
00:51:57,417 --> 00:52:01,733
When I was a little girl,
I had two big wishes.

611
00:52:01,754 --> 00:52:04,896
And that was first,
a hunting knife,

612
00:52:04,924 --> 00:52:06,907
and then, the gun.

613
00:52:06,927 --> 00:52:10,878
And when I turned 15,
I got the gun.

614
00:52:12,798 --> 00:52:15,747
And I turned out
to be a good shot.

615
00:52:15,767 --> 00:52:20,381
I only needed one bullet
to kill a goat or a pig.

616
00:52:22,773 --> 00:52:26,282
So little by little,
I was discovering...

617
00:52:26,311 --> 00:52:30,856
that it was great to grow up
like this in a very special way,

618
00:52:30,882 --> 00:52:33,228
and all the liberty I had.

619
00:52:40,691 --> 00:52:46,203
[ Woman ] As a child who grew up
here, the Galépagos was my oyster.

620
00:52:46,230 --> 00:52:49,976
I often say that
I've reaped all the benefits...

621
00:52:49,999 --> 00:52:53,917
of the decisions
that my parents made.

622
00:52:53,937 --> 00:52:58,481
You know, I didn't have to weigh the
pros and cons of coming to live here.

623
00:52:58,507 --> 00:53:01,924
I didn't bear the burden
of responsibility.

624
00:53:01,944 --> 00:53:04,425
I didn't bear the risk
of failure.

625
00:53:04,446 --> 00:53:07,089
I just lived it.

626
00:53:16,941 --> 00:53:20,323
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
Thursday, January 26.</i>

627
00:53:20,344 --> 00:53:22,451
<i>We are back with our friends
in the Galépagos,</i>

628
00:53:22,479 --> 00:53:25,520
<i>having returned
on our annual scientific voyage.</i>

629
00:53:25,549 --> 00:53:29,432
<i>And this has turned out
to be a very unusual day.</i>

630
00:53:29,452 --> 00:53:33,165
<i>Coming ashore on Floreana with gifts
and supplies for the Ritters,</i>

631
00:53:33,189 --> 00:53:38,803
<i>we encountered a strange sign, written
in what appears to be red lipstick.</i>

632
00:53:40,796 --> 00:53:43,142
<i>[ Reading As The Baroness]
Friends, whoever you are,</i>

633
00:53:43,165 --> 00:53:46,844
<i>two hours from here
lies the Hacienda Paradise,</i>

634
00:53:46,869 --> 00:53:50,981
<i>a lovely spot where the weary
traveler can rejoice...</i>

635
00:53:51,007 --> 00:53:56,324
<i>to find refreshing peace and
tranquillity on his way through life.</i>

636
00:53:56,345 --> 00:54:01,458
<i>In Paradise, you have
only one name-- friend.</i>

637
00:54:01,482 --> 00:54:03,862
<i>[ Reading As John Garth] We hardly
had time to take in this sign...</i>

638
00:54:03,884 --> 00:54:06,891
<i>before a flashing mirror signaled
to us from the Ritter homestead.</i>

639
00:54:06,920 --> 00:54:09,903
<i>The captain raced up there
in all haste.</i>

640
00:54:09,922 --> 00:54:12,999
<i>He returned about dusk
with a wild tale.</i>

641
00:54:13,027 --> 00:54:16,010
<i>There is now a baroness
living on Floreana...</i>

642
00:54:16,029 --> 00:54:19,274
<i>with several husbands
and a machine gun.</i>

643
00:54:19,298 --> 00:54:23,115
<i>And not long ago, a Norwegian had
run to the Ritters for protection,</i>

644
00:54:23,136 --> 00:54:25,640
<i>his clothes
torn from his body.</i>

645
00:54:25,671 --> 00:54:28,553
<i>This bears investigation
by all hands.</i>

646
00:54:32,477 --> 00:54:37,396
<i>At Captain Hancock's request, Dr. Ritter
took the group to the baroness's camp.</i>

647
00:54:37,415 --> 00:54:40,092
<i>The baroness speaks
eight languages...</i>

648
00:54:40,118 --> 00:54:46,005
<i>and claims as her uncles no lesser musicians
than Franz Liszt and Richard Wagner.</i>

649
00:54:46,023 --> 00:54:49,565
<i>The tales of machine guns
and terror do seem far-fetched.</i>

650
00:54:49,594 --> 00:54:53,444
<i>However she has no ideas of good
housekeeping or sanitation.</i>

651
00:54:53,464 --> 00:54:57,175
<i>We shuddered at the filth in
which she and her lovers live.</i>

652
00:54:59,169 --> 00:55:00,844
<i>Taking leave of the baroness,</i>

653
00:55:00,871 --> 00:55:03,820
<i>Ritter led us up a short trail
to a barbed wire fence...</i>

654
00:55:03,840 --> 00:55:07,087
<i>separating her establishment
from that of the Wittmers.</i>

655
00:55:07,111 --> 00:55:10,151
<i>Margret Wittmer is quite
a homemaker,</i>

656
00:55:10,179 --> 00:55:14,359
<i>an assertion which could not be
made of Dore, nor of the baroness.</i>

657
00:55:18,186 --> 00:55:20,429
<i>In the late afternoon,
we made the mistake...</i>

658
00:55:20,455 --> 00:55:25,739
<i>of bringing all three of the island's
groups aboard the Velero at the same time.</i>

659
00:55:25,760 --> 00:55:28,243
<i>Dore immediately
spoiled things...</i>

660
00:55:28,263 --> 00:55:32,773
<i>by mincing no words in telling the
baroness what she thought of her.</i>

661
00:55:32,800 --> 00:55:34,906
<i>For a few minutes
I feared trouble,</i>

662
00:55:34,935 --> 00:55:39,649
<i>until we averted this by keeping the
parties separate for the rest of the day.</i>

663
00:55:43,210 --> 00:55:46,921
<i>Early the next morning, we set
ashore at Black Beach anchorage,</i>

664
00:55:46,946 --> 00:55:51,958
<i>where Dr. Ritter appeared with a donkey
to pick up our huge pile of gifts.</i>

665
00:55:51,985 --> 00:55:55,629
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Captain Hancock had
brought generous presents for the Ritters,</i>

666
00:55:55,655 --> 00:55:59,972
<i>things which we islanders consider
among the treasures of the earth.</i>

667
00:55:59,993 --> 00:56:02,908
<i>But when the baroness heard
about these presents,</i>

668
00:56:02,928 --> 00:56:06,468
<i>her jealousy was aroused
and a war broke out.</i>

669
00:56:06,497 --> 00:56:09,003
<i>Going directly to the Ritters
with Philippson,</i>

670
00:56:09,033 --> 00:56:11,277
<i>the baroness demanded
that Ritter arrange...</i>

671
00:56:11,303 --> 00:56:15,312
<i>for what she called a fair
distribution of the gifts.</i>

672
00:56:15,340 --> 00:56:19,485
<i>Dr. Ritter blew up and threw
Philippson headfirst out the door.</i>

673
00:56:19,510 --> 00:56:24,054
<i>It is becoming more and more
uncomfortable on Floreana.</i>

674
00:56:24,081 --> 00:56:28,089
[ Fritz] The disaster for him
were the rich people who came.

675
00:56:28,117 --> 00:56:33,766
The money. And money destroys any
paradise of the world, yeah?

676
00:56:35,091 --> 00:56:37,336
They brought him
so many gifts...

677
00:56:37,361 --> 00:56:43,317
and they turned him back
to civilization.

678
00:56:43,333 --> 00:56:49,219
And this is the reason, in the philosophy
of Friedrich, why people make war.

679
00:56:49,237 --> 00:56:51,447
Only aggression.

680
00:56:51,473 --> 00:56:54,116
And behind aggression,

681
00:56:54,143 --> 00:56:59,256
the wish to have property...

682
00:56:59,280 --> 00:57:01,592
and the wish to have money.

683
00:57:01,616 --> 00:57:03,962
It's the same.
It was a war.

684
00:57:03,984 --> 00:57:06,330
More nothing than a war.

685
00:57:08,722 --> 00:57:11,898
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
Sunday, February 6, 1933.</i>

686
00:57:11,924 --> 00:57:13,999
<i>Today we leave Floreana,</i>

687
00:57:14,028 --> 00:57:17,706
<i>and we carry away with us several
impressions regarding our friends.</i>

688
00:57:17,730 --> 00:57:22,011
<i>First, the baroness seems
to be an accomplished, comely,</i>

689
00:57:22,033 --> 00:57:25,986
<i>quite loquacious, if neurotic
and unconventional lady,</i>

690
00:57:26,005 --> 00:57:28,681
<i>who could be very attractive
and companionable.</i>

691
00:57:28,707 --> 00:57:33,319
<i>Second, the Ritters not only resent
competition in the hermit business,</i>

692
00:57:33,344 --> 00:57:36,158
<i>but are inclined
to be troublemakers.</i>

693
00:57:36,182 --> 00:57:42,034
<i>Thirdly, the Wittmer family is really
succeeding in living off the land 100%,</i>

694
00:57:42,053 --> 00:57:44,831
<i>something the Ritters
have been unable to do...</i>

695
00:57:44,854 --> 00:57:48,738
<i>because of the generosity
of Captain Hancock and others.</i>

696
00:57:48,759 --> 00:57:54,112
<i>Lastly, go where you may, you cannot
escape the problem of social adjustment.</i>

697
00:57:56,032 --> 00:57:59,243
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] That Sunday,
following the departure of the Velero,</i>

698
00:57:59,268 --> 00:58:03,745
<i>unannounced and uninvited,
the baroness paid us a call...</i>

699
00:58:03,774 --> 00:58:06,848
<i>with the inevitable Philippson
as escort.</i>

700
00:58:06,876 --> 00:58:09,382
<i>She was in a fever
of excitement...</i>

701
00:58:09,412 --> 00:58:13,193
<i>at having met the first of the
millionaires she hoped to bait.</i>

702
00:58:13,216 --> 00:58:16,722
<i>And, without offering more
than a perfunctory greeting,</i>

703
00:58:16,751 --> 00:58:22,263
<i>she stared proudly at us and made
one of her silly pronouncements.</i>

704
00:58:22,290 --> 00:58:26,401
<i>[ Reading As The Baroness] Well, Captain
Hancock was absolutely charmed...</i>

705
00:58:26,427 --> 00:58:29,343
<i>by my hacienda,
and perhaps me,</i>

706
00:58:29,363 --> 00:58:32,973
<i>and when he comes back
we're going to make a film.</i>

707
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:36,678
<i>It shall be called
The Empress of Floreana.</i>

708
00:58:36,703 --> 00:58:39,050
<i>[ Laughs]
That's me.</i>

709
00:58:47,646 --> 00:58:52,499
[ Friedel ] It was funny, when the
yachts started to come more often,

710
00:58:52,519 --> 00:58:55,866
it was always a competition
who gets first on board.

711
00:58:57,123 --> 00:59:02,236
And among the Angermeyer
brothers, there was rivalry.

712
00:59:02,260 --> 00:59:06,337
So Karl complained that Gus was
always getting first there...

713
00:59:06,364 --> 00:59:10,076
and getting the most presents,
and so on.

714
00:59:10,100 --> 00:59:13,984
[ TePPY ] My mother, she got
everything from the boats.

715
00:59:14,004 --> 00:59:17,250
She wanted luxury, you know. She
wanted all the modern life, you know.

716
00:59:18,709 --> 00:59:20,347
My mother's from Ecuador.

717
00:59:20,376 --> 00:59:23,987
She was quite a few years younger than
my father. And she had a big dream.

718
00:59:24,013 --> 00:59:27,260
She married this German,
blue-eyed, blond-haired young man,

719
00:59:27,284 --> 00:59:29,893
what she thought
she was going to Europe.

720
00:59:29,920 --> 00:59:33,062
And she never went there. She lived in
the Galépagos Islands on the rock pile.

721
00:59:33,089 --> 00:59:34,899
I think she even came
in high-heeled shoes.

722
00:59:36,224 --> 00:59:38,605
My mother was only interested
in money, money, money.

723
00:59:38,627 --> 00:59:40,506
The more you get, the better.

724
00:59:40,529 --> 00:59:43,979
She took old rags on
to make herself poor...

725
00:59:43,999 --> 00:59:47,780
and went out rowing on this dinghy around
from yacht to yacht in the harbor.

726
00:59:47,803 --> 00:59:50,912
And said she had no milk, she had no
food for her kids, and everything.

727
00:59:50,939 --> 00:59:54,252
She came back rowing into the
dock, put her nice clothes on,

728
00:59:54,274 --> 00:59:57,382
went to town and sold
everything for high prices.

729
00:59:59,313 --> 01:00:01,762
Money was everything
for my mother.

730
01:00:01,783 --> 01:00:04,322
And my old man was
totally the opposite.

731
01:00:04,351 --> 01:00:07,927
<i>He lived off Luft und Liebe
und Sonnenschein.</i>

732
01:00:07,954 --> 01:00:10,232
Air, love and the sunshine.

733
01:00:10,256 --> 01:00:11,965
He said money,
he didn't need.

734
01:00:11,991 --> 01:00:15,499
"These islands are mine," he said.
"I'm the king. I do what I please."

735
01:00:25,638 --> 01:00:28,143
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Today the
governor of the Galépagos Islands...</i>

736
01:00:28,173 --> 01:00:33,355
<i>came over from San Cristébal with
seven soldiers and an interpreter.</i>

737
01:00:33,378 --> 01:00:38,195
<i>The purpose of his visit was to investigate
the accusations against the baroness...</i>

738
01:00:38,216 --> 01:00:42,225
<i>made months ago
by Ritter and Christian Stampa.</i>

739
01:00:42,253 --> 01:00:48,072
<i>The governor decided to hold his court
of inquiry in the Hacienda Paradiso.</i>

740
01:00:48,091 --> 01:00:53,512
<i>It seems that South Americans are easily
impressed by a European baroness...</i>

741
01:00:53,530 --> 01:00:59,282
<i>because in the end, he granted her a
title to four square miles of land...</i>

742
01:00:59,302 --> 01:01:01,579
<i>for her hotel.</i>

743
01:01:01,603 --> 01:01:05,886
<i>Afterwards, the governor granted
the Ritters and us a title too,</i>

744
01:01:05,908 --> 01:01:08,618
<i>but only for 50 acres each.</i>

745
01:01:08,644 --> 01:01:13,895
<i>Apparently we are only simple
settlers, not budding empresses.</i>

746
01:01:18,019 --> 01:01:20,467
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
One thing is now certain--</i>

747
01:01:20,488 --> 01:01:24,064
<i>the baroness has won access
to the spring at the Wittmers,</i>

748
01:01:24,091 --> 01:01:26,073
<i>which the governor
has declared free...</i>

749
01:01:26,093 --> 01:01:29,169
<i>for the common use
of both settlements.</i>

750
01:01:29,197 --> 01:01:31,371
<i>Now the Wittmers
will have the pleasure...</i>

751
01:01:31,398 --> 01:01:35,612
<i>of being overrun by her
and her men at all times...</i>

752
01:01:35,635 --> 01:01:38,642
<i>and with all impunity.</i>

753
01:01:38,671 --> 01:01:42,589
<i>[ Reading as Friedrich ] This decision
cannot fail to lead to open war...</i>

754
01:01:42,609 --> 01:01:45,615
<i>between the two households
at the caves,</i>

755
01:01:45,644 --> 01:01:49,891
<i>and it will only intensify
the baroness's mischievousness.</i>

756
01:01:52,417 --> 01:01:55,765
[Man Speaking Spanish]

757
01:03:02,499 --> 01:03:05,573
<i>[ Reading As Margret ] Mad things
are being said about the Galapagos.</i>

758
01:03:06,402 --> 01:03:08,009
<i>Captain Hancock has returned,</i>

759
01:03:08,038 --> 01:03:09,848
<i>bringing newspapers
and magazines...</i>

760
01:03:09,872 --> 01:03:13,517
<i>containing stories
that astonish us.</i>

761
01:03:13,543 --> 01:03:17,322
<i>Apparently the baroness
is not only an empress.</i>

762
01:03:17,345 --> 01:03:20,023
<i>She also has
a court of 12 noblemen,</i>

763
01:03:20,049 --> 01:03:22,554
<i>has created
a 'Terror regiment”...</i>

764
01:03:22,584 --> 01:03:27,265
<i>and has had Dr. Ritter taken
prisoner and led away in chains.</i>

765
01:03:27,289 --> 01:03:30,535
<i>We discuss it later with Dr.
Ritter, who laughs heartily.</i>

766
01:03:30,559 --> 01:03:33,132
<i>The baroness laughs about it
as well and says...</i>

767
01:03:33,161 --> 01:03:37,408
<i>she wonders who is responsible
for such tall tales.</i>

768
01:03:37,431 --> 01:03:40,040
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] I told the
Wittmers that it is more than probable...</i>

769
01:03:40,067 --> 01:03:42,777
<i>that the baroness herself
spread the rumors...</i>

770
01:03:42,802 --> 01:03:46,446
<i>merely to gain attention
and create a sensation...</i>

771
01:03:46,472 --> 01:03:49,548
<i>which should then
launch her hotel.</i>

772
01:03:49,577 --> 01:03:52,252
<i>[ Reading As Dore] She is revealing
herself to be a person...</i>

773
01:03:52,279 --> 01:03:55,820
whose <i>love of sensation
will stop at nothing.</i>

774
01:03:55,849 --> 01:04:00,427
<i>And now it seems she has drawn
even Captain Hancock into her web.</i>

775
01:04:00,452 --> 01:04:05,963
<i>Friedrich and I are shocked to learn that he
really does intend to make a film of the baroness.</i>

776
01:04:05,990 --> 01:04:08,906
<i>He says it is to be
a pirate film.</i>

777
01:04:14,399 --> 01:04:17,315
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
January 21, 1934.</i>

778
01:04:17,335 --> 01:04:20,181
<i>We came ashore this morning
at Post Office Bay...</i>

779
01:04:20,204 --> 01:04:23,381
<i>where the baroness and Philippson
met us for the filming.</i>

780
01:04:23,407 --> 01:04:25,479
<i>Our photographers
had planned a scenario...</i>

781
01:04:25,508 --> 01:04:29,188
<i>in which she would figure
in more or less a pirate role.</i>

782
01:04:29,213 --> 01:04:30,750
<i>AH hands pitched in,</i>

783
01:04:30,780 --> 01:04:33,889
<i>with First Officer Charles
Swett serving as cameraman,</i>

784
01:04:33,917 --> 01:04:35,455
<i>Emory Johnson directing...</i>

785
01:04:35,485 --> 01:04:37,659
<i>and playing
the baroness's paramour,</i>

786
01:04:37,687 --> 01:04:40,534
<i>and Ray Elliott,
our student zoologist,</i>

787
01:04:40,556 --> 01:04:42,538
<i>taking a secondary
female part...</i>

788
01:04:42,558 --> 01:04:46,533
<i>in spite of his miniature
and as yet colorless mustache.</i>

789
01:04:47,596 --> 01:04:50,580
<i>[ Projector Whirring ]</i>

790
01:06:33,695 --> 01:06:35,471
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
We have just received...</i>

791
01:06:35,496 --> 01:06:38,844
<i>some very intriguing information
about the baroness.</i>

792
01:06:38,866 --> 01:06:40,813
<i>Lorenz came to see us today...</i>

793
01:06:40,834 --> 01:06:43,841
<i>and in the strictest confidence
explained...</i>

794
01:06:43,870 --> 01:06:47,446
<i>that she is not really
a baroness after all.</i>

795
01:06:47,473 --> 01:06:51,755
<i>Apparently, she is married
to a Frenchman named Bousquet,</i>

796
01:06:51,777 --> 01:06:54,523
<i>who she left behind in Paris.</i>

797
01:06:54,548 --> 01:06:57,531
<i>She and Bousquet
met in Constantinople...</i>

798
01:06:57,550 --> 01:07:00,124
<i>where she was a dancer
before the war...</i>

799
01:07:00,153 --> 01:07:02,691
<i>and claims
to have been a spy.</i>

800
01:07:04,790 --> 01:07:07,898
<i>Lorenz then met the baroness
in Paris...</i>

801
01:07:07,925 --> 01:07:12,035
<i>and the two, with his money,
set up a boutique together.</i>

802
01:07:12,062 --> 01:07:16,983
<i>In the course of events they
hired Philippson as a salesman.</i>

803
01:07:17,001 --> 01:07:20,281
<i>Now, on Floreana,
the roles have been reversed...</i>

804
01:07:20,304 --> 01:07:24,414
<i>and the rest of his party regards
Lorenz as being just good enough...</i>

805
01:07:24,441 --> 01:07:27,858
<i>to take care of the livestock
and do house chores.</i>

806
01:07:30,079 --> 01:07:32,824
<i>[ Reading As Dore] Although both
men continue to sleep with her...</i>

807
01:07:32,849 --> 01:07:35,832
<i>together in one bed
when she commands it,</i>

808
01:07:35,851 --> 01:07:39,826
<i>Lorenz has been reduced
to little more than a slave.</i>

809
01:07:39,855 --> 01:07:43,636
<i>Curiously, he remains blindly
and hopelessly bewitched...</i>

810
01:07:43,659 --> 01:07:45,504
<i>by the baroness.</i>

811
01:09:38,097 --> 01:09:40,080
<i>[ Reading As The Baroness]
The man isn't born...</i>

812
01:09:40,100 --> 01:09:41,809
<i>who can resist me,</i>

813
01:09:41,835 --> 01:09:44,340
<i>and I am not afraid to say...</i>

814
01:09:44,371 --> 01:09:48,880
<i>that I find variety
the spice of life.</i>

815
01:09:56,247 --> 01:09:58,821
[José Speaking Spanish]

816
01:10:04,655 --> 01:10:06,660
It's a very special
picture.

817
01:10:06,691 --> 01:10:08,468
[Chuckles]

818
01:10:19,036 --> 01:10:23,455
[ Fritz] I think this is the only
picture that exists from Friedrich...

819
01:10:23,474 --> 01:10:25,786
where he is laughing a little.

820
01:10:25,809 --> 01:10:27,347
Yeah?

821
01:10:27,377 --> 01:10:29,016
And, uh, okay,

822
01:10:29,045 --> 01:10:31,220
this-- this seems...

823
01:10:31,247 --> 01:10:32,989
that there were...

824
01:10:35,818 --> 01:10:38,267
other...

825
01:10:38,287 --> 01:10:39,825
things going on.

826
01:10:39,856 --> 01:10:41,494
Yes?

827
01:10:41,523 --> 01:10:43,061
That there are mixed--

828
01:10:43,091 --> 01:10:45,266
Not only hate.

829
01:10:47,494 --> 01:10:50,969
[José Speaking Spanish]

830
01:11:32,471 --> 01:11:34,850
[Clucking ]

831
01:11:38,877 --> 01:11:41,154
[ Gil ]
It's interesting.

832
01:11:41,178 --> 01:11:44,755
The human being isn't
as easygoing as nature is.

833
01:11:45,715 --> 01:11:48,324
So growing here
in the Galépagos,

834
01:11:49,554 --> 01:11:52,765
with so little human influence,
was very easy.

835
01:11:55,358 --> 01:11:58,136
But inevitably
you become an adolescent...

836
01:11:59,396 --> 01:12:01,537
and you start getting interested
in your own species,

837
01:12:01,564 --> 01:12:04,571
which is of course
what happened with me also.

838
01:12:04,601 --> 01:12:06,639
And I started getting lies.

839
01:12:06,668 --> 01:12:08,239
I started getting,
you know, deceived.

840
01:12:08,269 --> 01:12:11,483
I started getting all kinds of
things that I wasn't used to at all.

841
01:12:11,508 --> 01:12:12,987
And that was hard.

842
01:12:15,344 --> 01:12:17,882
[Tui ]
Essentially, to varying extents,

843
01:12:17,912 --> 01:12:19,985
I think all the kids...

844
01:12:20,014 --> 01:12:21,552
that grow up
in that situation...

845
01:12:21,583 --> 01:12:24,031
are to some extent misfits.

846
01:12:25,220 --> 01:12:26,758
I certainly feel like...

847
01:12:26,788 --> 01:12:30,567
I'm still
a social apprentice.

848
01:12:31,758 --> 01:12:34,139
Just being
superficiallycorrect...

849
01:12:34,161 --> 01:12:36,005
is something that
doesn't come naturally,

850
01:12:36,029 --> 01:12:38,876
that I never learned the--

851
01:12:38,898 --> 01:12:41,608
You know, I never went
to finishing school.

852
01:12:41,634 --> 01:12:44,117
I didn't even go
to beginning school.

853
01:12:44,137 --> 01:12:46,915
So how could I finish
if I didn't begin?

854
01:12:46,939 --> 01:12:48,420
[ Laughing ]
You know?

855
01:12:49,375 --> 01:12:51,356
And I see the pattern
reemerge...

856
01:12:51,376 --> 01:12:54,520
in all sorts
of different people.

857
01:12:54,547 --> 01:12:56,027
So...

858
01:12:56,048 --> 01:12:58,827
once you become a grown-up,

859
01:12:58,851 --> 01:13:00,853
how do you then identify with,

860
01:13:00,884 --> 01:13:04,267
and most acutely,
who do you marry?

861
01:13:07,459 --> 01:13:10,602
[ Friedel ] Marga was
married to Carlos Kubler...

862
01:13:10,628 --> 01:13:13,737
and had the beautiful
daughter Carmen.

863
01:13:13,765 --> 01:13:18,775
But Marga was very unhappy
with Carlos Kubler.

864
01:13:18,802 --> 01:13:21,217
So Marga left him,

865
01:13:21,238 --> 01:13:22,876
left Carlos Kubler...

866
01:13:22,905 --> 01:13:25,445
and, um, later married...

867
01:13:25,475 --> 01:13:28,253
Karl Angermeyer.

868
01:13:28,277 --> 01:13:32,094
And then that was good
for Fritz, the youngest.

869
01:13:32,115 --> 01:13:35,223
Fritz married Carmen.

870
01:13:35,251 --> 01:13:37,996
[Gil ] One fine day, Carmen
just decided that was that.

871
01:13:38,020 --> 01:13:40,629
She was going to
be with Fritz.

872
01:13:40,656 --> 01:13:42,864
And she brought her few
belongings along the cliff...

873
01:13:42,892 --> 01:13:46,843
and just dropped them there and waited for
him to come back from-- from fishing.

874
01:13:48,230 --> 01:13:50,404
And in the afternoon
when he came in,

875
01:13:50,431 --> 01:13:53,176
he disembarked there
with Carmen waiting.

876
01:13:53,201 --> 01:13:55,979
And Carmen said, "I'm
coming to stay with you."

877
01:13:56,003 --> 01:13:58,954
And he looked at her and he said,
"Okay." And that was that.

878
01:14:02,610 --> 01:14:06,219
So I married one brother
and she married the other one.

879
01:14:09,182 --> 01:14:12,166
Karl was my father-in-law...

880
01:14:12,185 --> 01:14:14,497
and my brother-in-law.

881
01:14:15,522 --> 01:14:17,503
[Carmen Giggles]

882
01:14:34,822 --> 01:14:37,805
[Man Speaking Spanish]

883
01:15:51,360 --> 01:15:54,605
<i>[ Reading As Dore] The drought began
toward the end of February...</i>

884
01:15:54,629 --> 01:15:57,977
<i>and the rains are now
months overdue.</i>

885
01:15:58,966 --> 01:16:01,074
<i>Each day we scan the skies...</i>

886
01:16:01,102 --> 01:16:03,277
<i>for some sign of a cloud,</i>

887
01:16:03,304 --> 01:16:05,182
<i>but none come.</i>

888
01:16:05,205 --> 01:16:10,422
<i>Heat such as we have never known
scorches every living thing.</i>

889
01:16:10,445 --> 01:16:14,419
<i>We measure 120 degrees
in the shade.</i>

890
01:16:14,447 --> 01:16:16,929
<i>The spring,
our source of life,</i>

891
01:16:16,949 --> 01:16:19,261
<i>has become
a thin trickle of water...</i>

892
01:16:19,285 --> 01:16:22,600
<i>wearily crawling
out of its dry bed.</i>

893
01:16:22,622 --> 01:16:25,035
<i>The strong plants
have all withered...</i>

894
01:16:25,056 --> 01:16:30,410
<i>and the island is strewn with the carcasses
of animals the drought has killed.</i>

895
01:16:30,429 --> 01:16:34,142
<i>It exhales the odors
of decay and death.</i>

896
01:16:36,501 --> 01:16:39,679
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] Heinz
Wittmer comes to see us every week.</i>

897
01:16:39,705 --> 01:16:43,314
<i>His spring too has been
reduced to almost nothing,</i>

898
01:16:43,340 --> 01:16:46,791
<i>and his ground
is less good than ours.</i>

899
01:16:46,811 --> 01:16:49,920
<i>But he tells us that
at the Hacienda Paradise...</i>

900
01:16:49,947 --> 01:16:51,895
<i>things are much worse.</i>

901
01:16:51,916 --> 01:16:54,228
<i>Their garden no longer
produces foodstuffs...</i>

902
01:16:54,251 --> 01:16:58,498
<i>and the baroness has run through
all of their supplies.</i>

903
01:16:59,990 --> 01:17:04,602
<i>The generous yachts on which
her hotel speculation depends...</i>

904
01:17:04,627 --> 01:17:07,509
<i>have stopped
visiting our shores.</i>

905
01:17:07,530 --> 01:17:10,036
<i>Indeed,
as weeks become months...</i>

906
01:17:10,066 --> 01:17:12,708
<i>and still no ships
appear on the horizon,</i>

907
01:17:12,736 --> 01:17:17,883
<i>the baroness's disappointment
has been driven to extremes.</i>

908
01:17:19,573 --> 01:17:21,557
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
Lorenz has told us...</i>

909
01:17:21,577 --> 01:17:24,992
<i>of fearful quarrels
at Hacienda Paradiso.</i>

910
01:17:25,013 --> 01:17:27,496
<i>He has received so many
terrible beatings...</i>

911
01:17:27,516 --> 01:17:31,057
<i>that he cannot bear
to stay there any longer.</i>

912
01:17:31,085 --> 01:17:34,796
<i>Yet if Friedrich and I
were to take him in,</i>

913
01:17:34,821 --> 01:17:39,036
<i>it would only bring a mountain of
trouble upon us from the baroness.</i>

914
01:17:40,927 --> 01:17:42,909
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
After Ritter refused him,</i>

915
01:17:42,930 --> 01:17:47,178
<i>we saw we should have to give
Lorenz the asylum he desires.</i>

916
01:17:47,200 --> 01:17:50,310
<i>And now the baroness
comes to our gate each day...</i>

917
01:17:50,337 --> 01:17:52,476
<i>calling out for him.</i>

918
01:17:52,504 --> 01:17:57,481
<i>Time and again Lorenz is enticed by
her and disappears to the hacienda.</i>

919
01:17:57,509 --> 01:18:01,655
<i>Hours later he returns
and sits at our table, crying.</i>

920
01:18:05,985 --> 01:18:09,434
<i>[ Reading As Dore] It may be that
in a wild place like Floreana,</i>

921
01:18:09,453 --> 01:18:12,904
<i>the primitive character
in each person comes out,</i>

922
01:18:12,924 --> 01:18:16,842
so <i>that everybody shows
his own true face--</i>

923
01:18:16,862 --> 01:18:21,508
<i>a rare sight in this world,
and rather disconcerting.</i>

924
01:18:21,532 --> 01:18:25,711
<i>Although Heinz Wittmer
is a quiet and thoughtful man,</i>

925
01:18:25,735 --> 01:18:31,453
<i>yesterday he talked himself into a
raving fury against the baroness.</i>

926
01:18:31,474 --> 01:18:34,457
<i>We had never seen him
in this state before,</i>

927
01:18:34,476 --> 01:18:37,984
<i>and when he was done
he turned to Friedrich and said,</i>

928
01:18:38,014 --> 01:18:41,658
<i>"We must all get together
and do something.</i>

929
01:18:41,684 --> 01:18:43,995
<i>It is no use
appealing to the governor.</i>

930
01:18:44,019 --> 01:18:48,233
<i>We've got to take things
into our own hands now."</i>

931
01:18:51,826 --> 01:18:55,208
<i>Something has also changed
in Lorenz.</i>

932
01:18:55,229 --> 01:18:59,409
<i>I now sense in him a fierce
and burning desperation.</i>

933
01:18:59,433 --> 01:19:02,473
<i>I wonder whether there might
conceivably be a limit...</i>

934
01:19:02,501 --> 01:19:06,647
<i>beyond which even this captive
cannot be driven.</i>

935
01:19:08,776 --> 01:19:13,023
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

936
01:19:31,063 --> 01:19:34,046
[Birds Calling]

937
01:19:38,269 --> 01:19:40,410
[ Squawking ]

938
01:19:43,306 --> 01:19:45,289
[Clucking ]

939
01:20:18,790 --> 01:20:22,468
<i>[ Reading As Dore] We continue to
suffer under this oppressive drought...</i>

940
01:20:22,493 --> 01:20:24,497
<i>and for months
we haven't seen a soul...</i>

941
01:20:24,530 --> 01:20:27,513
<i>but for Heinz Wittmer
on his weekly visit.</i>

942
01:20:27,532 --> 01:20:31,381
<i>There is an atmosphere
of gathering evil...</i>

943
01:20:31,401 --> 01:20:34,284
<i>closing in
upon the island.</i>

944
01:20:34,305 --> 01:20:39,953
<i>Ten days ago, Friedrich and I were resting
in the stillness of the intense heat...</i>

945
01:20:39,977 --> 01:20:44,123
<i>when all at once a long
shriek gashed the silence.</i>

946
01:20:45,949 --> 01:20:50,459
<i>It was an outcry of such panic and
terror that it was hardly human,</i>

947
01:20:50,486 --> 01:20:53,026
<i>and yet it was
a woman's voice.</i>

948
01:20:53,055 --> 01:20:56,871
<i>It froze the marrow
in our bones.</i>

949
01:20:56,893 --> 01:21:00,365
<i>We expected to hear footsteps
rushing down the path toward us,</i>

950
01:21:00,395 --> 01:21:02,844
<i>but no one came.</i>

951
01:21:02,864 --> 01:21:07,146
<i>And I said, "Perhaps the drought is
playing havoc with our nerves. "</i>

952
01:21:08,403 --> 01:21:11,876
<i>The next day was the day
when Wittmer usually called,</i>

953
01:21:11,906 --> 01:21:13,615
<i>but he did not come.</i>

954
01:21:14,408 --> 01:21:15,946
<i>Then yesterday,</i>

955
01:21:15,976 --> 01:21:18,618
<i>Margret Wittmer
appeared instead.</i>

956
01:21:18,645 --> 01:21:21,629
<i>She was not with her husband,
but with Lorenz,</i>

957
01:21:21,648 --> 01:21:24,929
<i>and she told us
the strangest story.</i>

958
01:21:24,952 --> 01:21:28,333
<i>It sounded almost
to have been rehearsed.</i>

959
01:21:31,791 --> 01:21:33,773
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
Three days ago,</i>

960
01:21:33,792 --> 01:21:36,775
<i>we heard the sounds of visitors
at the baroness's compound...</i>

961
01:21:36,795 --> 01:21:41,714
<i>and soon after Madame herself appeared
at the gate, asking for Lorenz.</i>

962
01:21:41,733 --> 01:21:45,412
<i>When I told her that Lorenz
was out with Heinz, she said,</i>

963
01:21:45,437 --> 01:21:48,512
<i>"Please tell him that friends
of ours have sailed in,</i>

964
01:21:48,540 --> 01:21:50,613
<i>and we're going to Tahiti
with them.</i>

965
01:21:50,642 --> 01:21:55,027
<i>I hope that the South Seas will be a
better place to realize my plans.</i>

966
01:21:55,047 --> 01:21:57,824
<i>Lorenz is to look after
the things I've left behind...</i>

967
01:21:57,848 --> 01:22:00,228
<i>till I either return
or send word.</i>

968
01:22:00,250 --> 01:22:03,564
<i>Auf Wiedersehen,
or perhaps good-bye.”</i>

969
01:22:03,586 --> 01:22:07,835
<i>Then she turned on her heel and
strode away in her riding costume.</i>

970
01:22:09,392 --> 01:22:11,430
<i>It seemed too good
to be true,</i>

971
01:22:11,460 --> 01:22:14,343
<i>and I told myself
that it was only talk.</i>

972
01:22:14,364 --> 01:22:19,181
<i>But later that day Lorenz went to the
hacienda and the house was empty.</i>

973
01:22:19,201 --> 01:22:21,012
<i>Deserted.</i>

974
01:22:21,036 --> 01:22:23,781
<i>To convince himself
that they had really left,</i>

975
01:22:23,806 --> 01:22:26,185
<i>he went to check
Post Office Bay.</i>

976
01:22:28,210 --> 01:22:31,922
<i>After that we did not
see Lorenz for two days,</i>

977
01:22:31,946 --> 01:22:33,654
<i>and when he returned
this morning...</i>

978
01:22:33,681 --> 01:22:35,857
<i>he said that all he found
at Post Office Bay...</i>

979
01:22:35,884 --> 01:22:38,891
<i>were footprints and donkey
tracks in the sand.</i>

980
01:22:40,420 --> 01:22:43,531
<i>There seems to be
no trace of them on the island.</i>

981
01:22:43,559 --> 01:22:46,542
<i>The baroness and Philippson
are gone.</i>

982
01:22:49,997 --> 01:22:52,741
<i>[ Reading As Dore] As Margret
Wittmer ended her story,</i>

983
01:22:52,766 --> 01:22:57,811
<i>Lorenz assumed an oddly matter-of-fact
voice and coolly asked us...</i>

984
01:22:57,837 --> 01:23:01,287
<i>if</i> we <i>would buy some of the
baroness's things from him.</i>

985
01:23:01,307 --> 01:23:06,694
<i>He says she left him no money and he
is burning to get off the island.</i>

986
01:23:06,712 --> 01:23:11,062
<i>I find it curious that he feels
free to sell her things so quickly,</i>

987
01:23:11,083 --> 01:23:12,962
<i>but in the end...</i>

988
01:23:12,984 --> 01:23:16,960
<i>Friedrich and I decided
to go to Hacienda Paradiso,</i>

989
01:23:16,989 --> 01:23:21,372
<i>thinking there might be something
useful for us to buy there.</i>

990
01:23:21,393 --> 01:23:25,743
<i>On our way we stopped to see
the Wittmefls new house.</i>

991
01:23:25,763 --> 01:23:27,540
<i>It was the first time
I'd been there,</i>

992
01:23:27,565 --> 01:23:29,876
<i>and almost immediately...</i>

993
01:23:29,900 --> 01:23:34,649
<i>my eyes fell upon a beautiful
pink damask tablecloth.</i>

994
01:23:34,670 --> 01:23:38,350
<i>I had seen it before--
at the baroness's.</i>

995
01:23:40,208 --> 01:23:42,886
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] The whole
story seems like nothing but lies...</i>

996
01:23:42,913 --> 01:23:45,053
<i>from beginning to end.</i>

997
01:23:45,080 --> 01:23:48,725
<i>Certainly Margret's mention of the
yacht does not completely satisfy me.</i>

998
01:23:48,751 --> 01:23:50,732
<i>I've not seen a ship
in weeks,</i>

999
01:23:50,752 --> 01:23:54,534
<i>and if there'd been one here
I'd surely have seen it.</i>

1000
01:23:57,826 --> 01:23:59,807
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
The Hacienda Paradise...</i>

1001
01:23:59,828 --> 01:24:03,803
<i>was hardly more than a stone's throw
away from the Wittmer's house.</i>

1002
01:24:03,832 --> 01:24:06,644
<i>Lorenz and the Wittmers
led us through the door...</i>

1003
01:24:06,667 --> 01:24:11,883
<i>and I nearly screamed
at the sight before my eyes.</i>

1004
01:24:11,905 --> 01:24:16,325
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

1005
01:24:26,487 --> 01:24:28,489
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
On her bedside table...</i>

1006
01:24:28,520 --> 01:24:30,503
<i>there was an ashtray
containing the remains...</i>

1007
01:24:30,523 --> 01:24:34,474
<i>of the long-stemmed Russian cigarettes
the baroness always smoked.</i>

1008
01:24:34,493 --> 01:24:37,067
<i>And, tellingly,
beside this ashtray...</i>

1009
01:24:37,096 --> 01:24:40,239
<i>lay her most beloved
possession.</i>

1010
01:24:40,265 --> 01:24:43,374
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

1011
01:24:51,476 --> 01:24:56,692
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] The baroness had often
spoken of this one small possession.</i>

1012
01:24:56,714 --> 01:25:00,255
<i>She'd told me that she never
went anywhere without it.</i>

1013
01:25:00,283 --> 01:25:03,358
<i>And yet there it was.</i>

1014
01:25:05,021 --> 01:25:08,005
<i>Chilled, I hung back
in the doorway.</i>

1015
01:25:09,959 --> 01:25:12,874
<i>[ Reading As Margret] Dr. Ritter
immediately began opening...</i>

1016
01:25:12,894 --> 01:25:15,639
<i>various chests and boxes.</i>

1017
01:25:15,664 --> 01:25:18,648
<i>Why has he taken it
for granted so readily...</i>

1018
01:25:18,667 --> 01:25:21,707
<i>that the baroness
will not be coming back?</i>

1019
01:25:22,571 --> 01:25:24,142
<i>Sinister suspicions...</i>

1020
01:25:24,172 --> 01:25:27,246
<i>have begun to surface
in my mind.</i>

1021
01:25:27,274 --> 01:25:30,725
<i>I wonder if perhaps
Dr. Ritter and Lorenz...</i>

1022
01:25:30,745 --> 01:25:33,160
<i>share some terrible secret.</i>

1023
01:25:35,716 --> 01:25:37,698
<i>[ Reading As Dore] I no longer
have the least doubt...</i>

1024
01:25:37,718 --> 01:25:40,702
<i>but that the baroness
and Philippson were murdered.</i>

1025
01:25:40,721 --> 01:25:43,226
<i>I feel a great pity
for the baroness.</i>

1026
01:25:43,257 --> 01:25:48,575
<i>While she lived I would have given
anything to see her leave the island.</i>

1027
01:25:48,595 --> 01:25:50,804
<i>But now that she is dead,</i>

1028
01:25:50,831 --> 01:25:54,407
<i>I would give just as much
to see her back again.</i>

1029
01:25:54,434 --> 01:25:56,780
<i>And I know that henceforth...</i>

1030
01:25:56,802 --> 01:25:58,875
<i>I shall be possessed
by the dread...</i>

1031
01:25:58,904 --> 01:26:01,581
<i>that Friedrich and I
will be the next victims...</i>

1032
01:26:01,607 --> 01:26:04,613
<i>of the murderer
who stalks Floreana.</i>

1033
01:26:04,642 --> 01:26:08,526
<i>It is plain to me that for the
moment our very lives depend...</i>

1034
01:26:08,547 --> 01:26:12,089
<i>on our keeping our suspicions
to ourselves.</i>

1035
01:26:27,565 --> 01:26:30,811
[Claudio Speaking Spanish]

1036
01:26:37,840 --> 01:26:41,086
When you get down to it, everybody
had a motive to kill the baroness.

1037
01:26:42,845 --> 01:26:44,484
There are people
in this world...

1038
01:26:44,513 --> 01:26:46,963
that just beg to get killed.

1039
01:26:50,586 --> 01:26:53,569
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

1040
01:26:59,194 --> 01:27:02,145
I don't think that
there's any doubt...

1041
01:27:02,164 --> 01:27:04,908
that Lorenz did away with them
some way or another.

1042
01:27:04,933 --> 01:27:07,414
[Chuckles] Simply, guns
are available, you know,

1043
01:27:07,434 --> 01:27:10,008
and suddenly,
bang, bang, you know--

1044
01:27:11,071 --> 01:27:13,714
Well, Lorenz--
I doubt if Lorenz did it.

1045
01:27:13,741 --> 01:27:15,984
[ Gil ] Personally, I
could clearly feel...

1046
01:27:16,010 --> 01:27:20,156
that Margret Wittmer
knew a whole bit more.

1047
01:27:20,180 --> 01:27:23,824
She well may have had
to help out...

1048
01:27:23,850 --> 01:27:25,853
at precisely
hiding the body...

1049
01:27:25,884 --> 01:27:27,524
or something
of the sort.

1050
01:27:27,554 --> 01:27:29,934
Many things could have
happened, you know.

1051
01:27:29,956 --> 01:27:34,534
She could also maybe have gone off to Tahiti
and sank with the boat and never got there.

1052
01:27:41,932 --> 01:27:46,351
I would suspect that old man
Wittmer did it. [Chuckles]

1053
01:27:46,370 --> 01:27:51,723
[ Gil ] It's hardly mentioned at
all the possibility of suicide.

1054
01:27:51,741 --> 01:27:56,023
But looking at the way she lived and
everything, I think it's very possible.

1055
01:28:22,304 --> 01:28:25,287
<i>[Thunder Rumbling ]</i>

1056
01:28:30,328 --> 01:28:33,711
<i>[ Reading As Friedrich ] The
first rains came on April 21.</i>

1057
01:28:34,632 --> 01:28:36,910
<i>And we have
come back to life...</i>

1058
01:28:36,934 --> 01:28:38,916
<i>here on Floreana.</i>

1059
01:28:45,775 --> 01:28:49,887
<i>Lorenz's desire to leave the island
and make his way back to Germany...</i>

1060
01:28:49,912 --> 01:28:52,361
<i>has reached a fever pitch.</i>

1061
01:28:52,382 --> 01:28:55,126
<i>Today I helped him write
a few lines of English...</i>

1062
01:28:55,151 --> 01:28:58,134
<i>to be nailed to the barrel
at Post Office Bay.</i>

1063
01:28:58,152 --> 01:28:59,793
<i>His message--</i>

1064
01:28:59,822 --> 01:29:03,295
<i>"There is a young man on
Floreana who begs any ship...</i>

1065
01:29:03,325 --> 01:29:06,138
<i>for an opportunity
to leave this island.</i>

1066
01:29:06,161 --> 01:29:10,341
<i>I live inland off the trail
that is marked in red.</i>

1067
01:29:10,365 --> 01:29:13,473
<i>Signed, Rudolf Lorenz."</i>

1068
01:29:34,485 --> 01:29:36,023
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
Months have passed...</i>

1069
01:29:36,055 --> 01:29:38,367
<i>without a single ship
touching our shores.</i>

1070
01:29:38,390 --> 01:29:41,272
<i>But today a boat
has come at last--</i>

1071
01:29:41,293 --> 01:29:43,708
<i>a boat for Lorenz.</i>

1072
01:29:43,730 --> 01:29:46,473
<i>It is the Dinamita,
a small fishing vessel...</i>

1073
01:29:46,497 --> 01:29:50,038
<i>owned by a Norwegian living
on the island of Santa Cruz,</i>

1074
01:29:50,067 --> 01:29:52,482
<i>a man named Nuggerud.</i>

1075
01:29:52,504 --> 01:29:56,149
<i>Nuggerud has agreed to take
Lorenz as far as Santa Cruz,</i>

1076
01:29:56,174 --> 01:29:59,181
<i>where he'll be able to
catch the ship for Guayaquil.</i>

1077
01:29:59,211 --> 01:30:02,855
<i>Meanwhile, Nuggerud
has a journalist on board,</i>

1078
01:30:02,880 --> 01:30:06,353
<i>a Swedish writer
named Rolf Blomberg.</i>

1079
01:30:06,383 --> 01:30:08,797
<i>Blomberg wants to have
a look at Floreana...</i>

1080
01:30:08,818 --> 01:30:12,702
<i>and expressed the intention
of visiting the baroness.</i>

1081
01:30:14,691 --> 01:30:18,107
<i>[ Man Reading] When no grim pirate
queen bearing a revolver...</i>

1082
01:30:18,128 --> 01:30:20,303
<i>came to greet us
in Post Office Bay,</i>

1083
01:30:20,330 --> 01:30:22,938
we <i>quickly made our way
to the Wittmers' house...</i>

1084
01:30:22,965 --> 01:30:27,611
<i>where Lorenz informed us that
the baroness had ”disappeared.”</i>

1085
01:30:27,635 --> 01:30:30,208
<i>I managed to get from them
the mysterious story,</i>

1086
01:30:30,237 --> 01:30:32,720
<i>which did not quite add up--</i>

1087
01:30:32,740 --> 01:30:34,915
<i>the yacht nobody had seen,</i>

1088
01:30:34,942 --> 01:30:39,486
<i>Lorenz selling the house and all its
contents to the Wittmers and the Ritters.</i>

1089
01:30:40,182 --> 01:30:41,719
<i>In any event,</i>

1090
01:30:41,749 --> 01:30:44,925
<i>it had been four months since the
island queen's disappearance...</i>

1091
01:30:44,951 --> 01:30:47,936
<i>and we appear to be
Lorenz's liberators,</i>

1092
01:30:47,955 --> 01:30:50,301
<i>come to take him away
from paradise...</i>

1093
01:30:50,324 --> 01:30:53,068
<i>and return him once again
to earth.</i>

1094
01:30:54,961 --> 01:30:58,378
<i>[ Reading As Dore] Blomberg quizzed
us incessantly about the baroness,</i>

1095
01:30:58,399 --> 01:31:00,379
<i>and it was
through this man...</i>

1096
01:31:00,399 --> 01:31:03,783
<i>that the story of her disappearance
went out into the world.</i>

1097
01:31:03,804 --> 01:31:07,652
<i>Friedrich and I hinted
at what we thought,</i>

1098
01:31:07,673 --> 01:31:10,349
<i>but we were careful
and did not feel yet...</i>

1099
01:31:10,374 --> 01:31:12,949
<i>that we could say much
on the matter.</i>

1100
01:31:12,978 --> 01:31:16,428
<i>For his part,
Lorenz looked gloomy.</i>

1101
01:31:16,448 --> 01:31:18,224
<i>Just before setting sail...</i>

1102
01:31:18,249 --> 01:31:21,233
<i>he whispered to me
in a low tone,</i>

1103
01:31:21,252 --> 01:31:26,228
<i>"I don't know why, but I'm
afraid of this trip somehow.”</i>

1104
01:31:34,732 --> 01:31:36,804
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
Dr. Ritter came to us today,</i>

1105
01:31:36,833 --> 01:31:41,344
<i>bringing some mail that was left
in Post Office Bay a few days ago.</i>

1106
01:31:41,371 --> 01:31:46,325
<i>Among the letters is an alarming
note from Blomberg in Santa Cruz.</i>

1107
01:31:47,810 --> 01:31:49,348
<i>[ Reading As Rolf]
The three of us set sail...</i>

1108
01:31:49,378 --> 01:31:51,257
<i>for Santa Cruz Island.</i>

1109
01:31:51,280 --> 01:31:52,920
<i>However, along the way,</i>

1110
01:31:52,949 --> 01:31:56,593
we <i>passed a big ship on a
hard tack for San Cristébal.</i>

1111
01:31:56,620 --> 01:32:01,072
<i>Lorenz saw this ship as his chance
to get to the mainland quickly.</i>

1112
01:32:01,089 --> 01:32:03,698
<i>So as soon as we anchored here
on Santa Cruz,</i>

1113
01:32:03,725 --> 01:32:07,540
<i>he began begging Nuggerud to set
out at once for San Cristébal...</i>

1114
01:32:07,562 --> 01:32:11,947
<i>so he could catch the ship
before it left for Guayaquil.</i>

1115
01:32:11,967 --> 01:32:14,950
[ Carmen ] Lorenz, I just saw
him when he came ashore.

1116
01:32:16,537 --> 01:32:19,350
It was a very unfriendly day
of July.

1117
01:32:19,374 --> 01:32:21,081
Rough seas.

1118
01:32:22,208 --> 01:32:23,986
You felt
that he wanted nobody.

1119
01:32:24,011 --> 01:32:28,429
He just stalked off, you know,
went off with his suitcase.

1120
01:32:28,448 --> 01:32:32,092
And he was very much in a hurry
to go on that boat.

1121
01:32:32,117 --> 01:32:34,829
And Nuggerud said, "I can't."

1122
01:32:34,855 --> 01:32:37,997
<i>[ Reading As Blomberg ] Nuggerud
was not very keen on the subject,</i>

1123
01:32:38,023 --> 01:32:41,201
<i>for it was Friday the 13th.</i>

1124
01:32:50,634 --> 01:32:53,140
<i>[ Reading As Blomberg ]
However, Lorenz kept pleading,</i>

1125
01:32:53,171 --> 01:32:57,920
<i>and finally, after he offered 50 sucres
for the trip if they left at once,</i>

1126
01:32:57,941 --> 01:33:00,585
<i>Nuggerud agreed.</i>

1127
01:33:02,679 --> 01:33:07,098
<i>Just at daybreak on the 13th,
we saw them set sail.</i>

1128
01:33:07,117 --> 01:33:12,435
<i>I am sorry to say that no one has
seen them or the Dinamita since.</i>

1129
01:33:19,394 --> 01:33:20,931
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
We are shattered.</i>

1130
01:33:20,962 --> 01:33:24,140
<i>Boats have gone out
in search of the Dinamita...</i>

1131
01:33:24,166 --> 01:33:27,582
<i>in hopes that they have been stranded
on one of the other islands.</i>

1132
01:33:27,603 --> 01:33:30,916
<i>But so far there's been
no trace of them.</i>

1133
01:33:33,976 --> 01:33:36,583
<i>There has been no news either
from Tahiti...</i>

1134
01:33:36,610 --> 01:33:40,356
<i>where the baroness and Philippson
were supposed to be going.</i>

1135
01:33:40,380 --> 01:33:44,629
<i>Everyone seems to have
disappeared without a trace.</i>

1136
01:33:51,290 --> 01:33:54,274
[ Seal Barking ]

1137
01:34:05,138 --> 01:34:09,112
[ Friedel ] I was dreaming
about leaving the island.

1138
01:34:10,743 --> 01:34:12,348
I had looked
on the map...

1139
01:34:12,377 --> 01:34:16,830
and seen that the Galépagos
were there,

1140
01:34:16,848 --> 01:34:19,353
just like little spots
from a fly.

1141
01:34:23,120 --> 01:34:27,835
I was very keen on
seeing the world.

1142
01:34:27,858 --> 01:34:32,812
And on the beach I had a
friend-- Teppy Angermeyer.

1143
01:34:32,830 --> 01:34:36,211
We used to talk together
and discuss.

1144
01:34:36,232 --> 01:34:40,048
And he said, "I want to
get away from here."

1145
01:34:40,069 --> 01:34:43,816
And then I used to say,
"Me too. But how?"

1146
01:34:43,840 --> 01:34:47,724
And then he said,
"Well, we need a boat."

1147
01:34:49,812 --> 01:34:52,590
[ TePPY ]
My older brother had left.

1148
01:34:52,614 --> 01:34:58,070
He met a girl on a yacht and fell in love and
her parents helped my brother out of here.

1149
01:35:00,055 --> 01:35:02,663
So I wished to go out
and see the world also.

1150
01:35:02,690 --> 01:35:05,732
You get to that age where you get
curious and you want to see it.

1151
01:35:08,930 --> 01:35:11,503
[ Friedel ]
So we were dreamers.

1152
01:35:11,532 --> 01:35:16,783
But life was getting
sort of complicated for me.

1153
01:35:18,171 --> 01:35:22,453
<i>Our neighbors, the Kastdakzns,
had one son, Ni.</i>

1154
01:35:24,244 --> 01:35:29,927
He was 15 years older than me
and he needed a wife.

1155
01:35:30,983 --> 01:35:33,898
In fact, we got rings on.

1156
01:35:33,918 --> 01:35:36,026
But I was getting cold feet...

1157
01:35:36,055 --> 01:35:40,164
and was wondering how can I
get out of this...

1158
01:35:40,190 --> 01:35:42,299
difficult situation.

1159
01:35:42,328 --> 01:35:44,809
Because I did not love Alf.

1160
01:35:47,765 --> 01:35:51,945
And suddenly there was
a very special solution.

1161
01:35:54,605 --> 01:36:00,219
Here came this yacht sailing
with Forrest Nelson on board.

1162
01:36:00,244 --> 01:36:05,665
And he asked me to come with him
and he asked me to marry him.

1163
01:36:05,682 --> 01:36:09,862
And then I thought quickly,
"Oh. This is an adventure!

1164
01:36:09,886 --> 01:36:13,838
This is a good idea.
Why not try it?"

1165
01:36:13,856 --> 01:36:16,269
And, uh, so I did.

1166
01:36:18,660 --> 01:36:21,165
[Chuckles]
They were a bit upset.

1167
01:36:21,197 --> 01:36:25,342
"Oh, you are just adventurous and
you are irresponsible," they said.

1168
01:36:25,366 --> 01:36:28,110
I said, “Okay.

1169
01:36:28,135 --> 01:36:31,712
I'll accept that
and be irresponsible.

1170
01:36:31,738 --> 01:36:33,584
And I'm going. Bye-bye?'

1171
01:36:33,608 --> 01:36:35,850
And that was it.

1172
01:36:39,713 --> 01:36:42,357
I started
a complete new life.

1173
01:36:43,649 --> 01:36:48,399
It was a great adventure
and he put me on as a sailor.

1174
01:36:48,422 --> 01:36:51,268
I thought
it was quite romantic.

1175
01:36:51,291 --> 01:36:56,644
And from Galépagos we sailed
all the way up to San Diego.

1176
01:36:59,799 --> 01:37:02,749
It was great
and I was very, very happy,

1177
01:37:02,768 --> 01:37:05,614
and I thought he wanted
to continue sailing...

1178
01:37:05,637 --> 01:37:07,380
and maybe sail
around the world...

1179
01:37:07,405 --> 01:37:09,478
and stop
and work some places...

1180
01:37:09,507 --> 01:37:12,081
and earn a little money
to go on.

1181
01:37:12,110 --> 01:37:16,255
But the reality was that in San
Diego he wanted to sell the boat...

1182
01:37:16,280 --> 01:37:18,820
and he wanted to
come back to the Galépagos...

1183
01:37:18,850 --> 01:37:20,388
and start a hotel.

1184
01:37:20,417 --> 01:37:21,898
And so we did.

1185
01:37:24,220 --> 01:37:27,226
This was in 1960...

1186
01:37:27,256 --> 01:37:30,435
and there was not
a single hotel.

1187
01:37:32,662 --> 01:37:34,644
I felt sad.

1188
01:37:34,664 --> 01:37:36,839
But I couldn't say
anything.

1189
01:37:36,866 --> 01:37:38,472
I was so young.

1190
01:37:38,501 --> 01:37:40,642
And so I just accepted it.

1191
01:37:40,670 --> 01:37:43,346
But my heart was bleeding.

1192
01:38:08,978 --> 01:38:12,395
<i>[ Reading As Dore] Only four
adults remain on the island,</i>

1193
01:38:12,416 --> 01:38:15,297
<i>and a strange mood
has come over Friedrich.</i>

1194
01:38:17,454 --> 01:38:20,232
<i>Yesterday he turned to me
and said,</i>

1195
01:38:20,256 --> 01:38:24,072
<i>"I think I shall go on
to my end on Floreana.</i>

1196
01:38:24,093 --> 01:38:26,939
<i>I have found here
what I came to find,</i>

1197
01:38:26,962 --> 01:38:30,038
<i>and this is
where I hope to die.”</i>

1198
01:38:30,066 --> 01:38:32,777
<i>Happily, this new mood...</i>

1199
01:38:32,802 --> 01:38:36,718
<i>has allowed us to find harmony
and peace together,</i>

1200
01:38:36,738 --> 01:38:41,248
<i>and Friedrich has become
considerate and tender.</i>

1201
01:38:41,275 --> 01:38:45,319
<i>A stillness that we have never
known before unites us.</i>

1202
01:38:49,917 --> 01:38:53,025
<i>[ Reading As Margret ] Dr. Ritter
visited today and confided to us...</i>

1203
01:38:53,052 --> 01:38:56,093
<i>that he and Dore
are always quarreling now...</i>

1204
01:38:56,122 --> 01:38:58,229
<i>and it is getting
on his nerves.</i>

1205
01:38:58,257 --> 01:39:03,234
<i>He says that the poor woman's not herself
and has become extremely difficult.</i>

1206
01:39:04,965 --> 01:39:07,846
<i>[ Reading As Heinz] Dr. Ritter tells us
that they are running short of food.</i>

1207
01:39:07,866 --> 01:39:13,253
<i>The rains that broke the drought have
come too late to save his crops.</i>

1208
01:39:13,272 --> 01:39:15,311
<i>Even their source of eggs
is gone.</i>

1209
01:39:15,340 --> 01:39:18,119
<i>Dore fed his chickens
spoiled pig meat...</i>

1210
01:39:18,143 --> 01:39:20,386
<i>and now they are all dead.</i>

1211
01:39:20,412 --> 01:39:22,986
<i>Margret and I
visited Friedo today...</i>

1212
01:39:23,015 --> 01:39:27,434
<i>and found the doctor boiling these
dead chickens for future use.</i>

1213
01:39:27,452 --> 01:39:29,557
<i>He offered us
a jar of the chicken,</i>

1214
01:39:29,586 --> 01:39:33,505
<i>insisting that the poison
had been boiled out.</i>

1215
01:39:33,524 --> 01:39:36,736
<i>We thanked him hastily
and refused the offer.</i>

1216
01:39:40,797 --> 01:39:42,972
<i>[ Reading As Dore] Yesterday,
with great reluctance,</i>

1217
01:39:42,999 --> 01:39:46,347
<i>we decided that we must overcome
our aversion to meat...</i>

1218
01:39:46,369 --> 01:39:49,717
<i>and have one of the boiled
chickens for dinner.</i>

1219
01:39:49,738 --> 01:39:53,747
<i>We took every possible precaution
in preparing the poultry.</i>

1220
01:39:53,776 --> 01:39:56,281
<i>Friedrich tried
only a little.</i>

1221
01:39:56,311 --> 01:39:58,418
<i>I ate more of it.</i>

1222
01:39:59,381 --> 01:40:00,919
<i>A few hours later...</i>

1223
01:40:00,950 --> 01:40:05,130
<i>Friedrich lay down, complaining
of feeling rather ill.</i>

1224
01:40:05,154 --> 01:40:09,731
<i>Soon nausea set in
and agonizing pains.</i>

1225
01:40:09,757 --> 01:40:13,503
<i>The whole of that night was spent
trying to stem the tide of poison,</i>

1226
01:40:13,527 --> 01:40:16,842
<i>which was overwhelming
his body.</i>

1227
01:40:16,864 --> 01:40:20,111
<i>At dawn he asked me to
read Nietzsche to him...</i>

1228
01:40:20,134 --> 01:40:25,315
<i>and when I came to one of his favorite
passages he said in a faint voice,</i>

1229
01:40:25,338 --> 01:40:27,844
<i>"Mark those lines, Dore.</i>

1230
01:40:27,875 --> 01:40:31,257
<i>Remember them always
in memory of me.”</i>

1231
01:40:32,412 --> 01:40:34,723
<i>Despair surged over me.</i>

1232
01:40:34,746 --> 01:40:36,557
<i>Friedrich was dying.</i>

1233
01:40:36,582 --> 01:40:39,964
<i>And what could I do
at Friedo alone?</i>

1234
01:40:41,420 --> 01:40:44,403
[Octavio Speaking Spanish]

1235
01:40:57,202 --> 01:40:59,844
<i>[ Reading As Dore] By the time
Margret and I got back to Friedo,</i>

1236
01:40:59,870 --> 01:41:05,450
<i>Friedrich '5 tongue was so badly swollen
that he could no longer speak clearly.</i>

1237
01:41:05,475 --> 01:41:07,514
<i>I sat beside him
through the night,</i>

1238
01:41:07,544 --> 01:41:12,293
<i>praying that somehow
he might get well again.</i>

1239
01:41:12,315 --> 01:41:15,459
<i>At dawn, Friedrich
suddenly sat up.</i>

1240
01:41:15,486 --> 01:41:18,935
<i>He stretched out
both his arms toward me.</i>

1241
01:41:18,954 --> 01:41:22,531
<i>All trace of pain and torment
had vanished from his face,</i>

1242
01:41:22,558 --> 01:41:25,371
<i>which was transfigured
with a look so lucid,</i>

1243
01:41:25,395 --> 01:41:28,571
<i>so triumphant,
so calm, so tender...</i>

1244
01:41:28,597 --> 01:41:33,711
<i>that I could only gaze and gaze upon
him like one who sees a miracle.</i>

1245
01:41:34,802 --> 01:41:37,844
<i>But then he fell back
on the pillows,</i>

1246
01:41:37,873 --> 01:41:41,084
<i>and before I was able
to utter a sound...</i>

1247
01:41:41,109 --> 01:41:43,853
<i>he was gone.</i>

1248
01:41:55,856 --> 01:41:58,304
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
When Dore and I reached Friedo,</i>

1249
01:41:58,325 --> 01:42:02,070
<i>Friedrich looked as if he was
in excruciating pain.</i>

1250
01:42:02,094 --> 01:42:06,137
<i>His one comprehensible remark was
to point out the bitter irony...</i>

1251
01:42:06,165 --> 01:42:08,306
<i>that he, a vegetarian,</i>

1252
01:42:08,334 --> 01:42:11,147
<i>was dying
from meat poisoning.</i>

1253
01:42:11,170 --> 01:42:13,151
<i>Then he made
an immense effort,</i>

1254
01:42:13,171 --> 01:42:15,381
<i>felt for the pencil and paper
by his bed...</i>

1255
01:42:15,407 --> 01:42:17,251
<i>and wrote his last sentence--</i>

1256
01:42:17,275 --> 01:42:21,056
<i>"I curse you
with my dying breath.”</i>

1257
01:42:21,079 --> 01:42:25,829
<i>With that he looked up at Dore,
his eyes gleaming with hate.</i>

1258
01:42:25,851 --> 01:42:29,131
<i>He struggled against the shot of
morphine that Dore gave him...</i>

1259
01:42:29,153 --> 01:42:31,134
<i>and repelled
with blows and kicks...</i>

1260
01:42:31,155 --> 01:42:33,865
<i>every effort
she made to touch him.</i>

1261
01:42:33,890 --> 01:42:35,873
<i>Hours went by like this...</i>

1262
01:42:35,893 --> 01:42:40,209
<i>until he at last collapsed
on his pillows and was gone.</i>

1263
01:42:59,147 --> 01:43:03,328
<i>[ Reading As Heinz ] The next day,
Harry and I buried Dr. Ritter's body.</i>

1264
01:43:03,352 --> 01:43:05,333
<i>We wrapped it up
in a piece of linen cloth...</i>

1265
01:43:05,353 --> 01:43:09,499
<i>and transported it to a spot in the
garden where we had prepared a grave.</i>

1266
01:43:09,524 --> 01:43:11,766
<i>We then buried him
between the stones...</i>

1267
01:43:11,791 --> 01:43:16,039
<i>that he had removed from the
ground with so much trouble.</i>

1268
01:43:16,062 --> 01:43:20,173
<i>[ Reading As Margret ] As Heinz placed
a simple cross on Dr. Ritter's grave,</i>

1269
01:43:20,200 --> 01:43:21,841
<i>I wondered to myself...</i>

1270
01:43:21,868 --> 01:43:25,647
<i>about Dora's inexplicable delay
in coming to get us...</i>

1271
01:43:25,670 --> 01:43:28,120
<i>once she saw he was so ill.</i>

1272
01:43:28,141 --> 01:43:30,522
<i>Why on earth
did she wait so long...</i>

1273
01:43:30,544 --> 01:43:33,492
<i>when every moment
was so vital?</i>

1274
01:43:33,512 --> 01:43:37,794
<i>Also, while Dore assured me
that she had eaten the meat too,</i>

1275
01:43:37,815 --> 01:43:41,699
<i>she never looked anything
but perfectly normal.</i>

1276
01:43:46,458 --> 01:43:48,906
<i>[ Reading As Dore ] The linen
I had brought from Germany...</i>

1277
01:43:48,926 --> 01:43:51,773
<i>made Friedrich '5 shroud.</i>

1278
01:43:51,796 --> 01:43:54,642
<i>The atmosphere was now
full of ghostliness...</i>

1279
01:43:54,665 --> 01:43:57,774
<i>and I became possessed
not only with the feeling...</i>

1280
01:43:57,801 --> 01:44:00,511
<i>that the island
was a haunted ground,</i>

1281
01:44:00,536 --> 01:44:03,577
<i>but that I should be
its next victim.</i>

1282
01:44:05,208 --> 01:44:08,556
<i>That night I took out
pen and paper.</i>

1283
01:44:08,578 --> 01:44:12,394
<i>"Friedrich is dead,"
I wrote to Captain Hancock.</i>

1284
01:44:12,415 --> 01:44:14,396
<i>"Please help me."</i>

1285
01:44:20,656 --> 01:44:22,865
[José Speaking Spanish]

1286
01:44:31,165 --> 01:44:33,670
[ TePPY ]
I find it very mysterious.

1287
01:44:33,701 --> 01:44:37,744
And as a child, because we had very little
with deaths here and this sort of thing,

1288
01:44:37,771 --> 01:44:40,084
then you worry,
you know.

1289
01:44:40,108 --> 01:44:45,061
You can kind of get afraid and think,
you know, "What's it all about?"

1290
01:44:48,548 --> 01:44:53,001
[Jorge Speaking Spanish]

1291
01:45:30,487 --> 01:45:32,469
[Laughing]

1292
01:45:38,095 --> 01:45:41,271
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
Sunday, December 2, 1934.</i>

1293
01:45:41,297 --> 01:45:45,613
<i>Just before Thanksgiving, Captain Hancock's
telephone rang late in the night.</i>

1294
01:45:45,634 --> 01:45:47,239
<i>It was the press.</i>

1295
01:45:47,269 --> 01:45:51,483
<i>Two bodies have been found dead
beside an overturned boat...</i>

1296
01:45:51,506 --> 01:45:55,151
<i>on the black lava sands
of Marchena Island.</i>

1297
01:45:55,177 --> 01:45:57,557
<i>A few days later
we were on our way south,</i>

1298
01:45:57,579 --> 01:46:00,564
<i>our ship steering
straight for the Galépagos.</i>

1299
01:46:01,816 --> 01:46:04,128
<i>This time,
as the holidays are upon us,</i>

1300
01:46:04,152 --> 01:46:06,395
<i>several wives
joined our crew.</i>

1301
01:46:10,591 --> 01:46:12,971
<i>At 2:00 p.m. today
we dropped anchor...</i>

1302
01:46:12,993 --> 01:46:14,941
<i>and climbed ashore
on Marchena,</i>

1303
01:46:14,961 --> 01:46:18,572
<i>that strange, dead remnant
of an ancient volcano...</i>

1304
01:46:18,599 --> 01:46:22,812
<i>which stands 60 miles north ward
of its nearest Galépagos neighbor.</i>

1305
01:46:24,069 --> 01:46:25,846
<i>Far above the reach
of the waves...</i>

1306
01:46:25,873 --> 01:46:29,152
we <i>could see the wreck of a
dinghy and a bamboo pole...</i>

1307
01:46:29,174 --> 01:46:32,955
<i>on which an old gray coat
had flown as a distress signal.</i>

1308
01:46:32,978 --> 01:46:35,620
<i>Slowly, soberly,</i>

1309
01:46:35,647 --> 01:46:37,595
we <i>climbed
the hard-packed sand...</i>

1310
01:46:37,616 --> 01:46:41,567
<i>and therein front of us a
gruesome sight presented itself--</i>

1311
01:46:44,690 --> 01:46:49,403
<i>the mummified form of Nuggerud,
the Norwegian sea captain.</i>

1312
01:46:54,932 --> 01:46:59,579
<i>A short distance away lay
all that was left of Lorenz.</i>

1313
01:46:59,604 --> 01:47:02,416
<i>He was dressed just as
when we last saw him.</i>

1314
01:47:02,439 --> 01:47:04,682
<i>I would have known
him anywhere--</i>

1315
01:47:04,708 --> 01:47:07,021
<i>knit sweater, gray vest,</i>

1316
01:47:07,044 --> 01:47:10,926
<i>overalls cut to shorts
and hand-stitched at the knees.</i>

1317
01:47:12,515 --> 01:47:14,929
<i>As I gazed on Lorenz's body,</i>

1318
01:47:14,950 --> 01:47:17,992
<i>I could not help but wonder if
I was looking into the face...</i>

1319
01:47:18,021 --> 01:47:21,369
<i>of the murderer of
the baroness and Philippson.</i>

1320
01:47:21,390 --> 01:47:23,770
<i>But if so,
what swift retribution...</i>

1321
01:47:23,792 --> 01:47:27,938
<i>to overtake him in the very act
of fleeing from his crime,</i>

1322
01:47:27,963 --> 01:47:29,966
<i>and what seeming injustice...</i>

1323
01:47:29,997 --> 01:47:32,606
<i>to involve Nuggerud,
an innocent man,</i>

1324
01:47:32,634 --> 01:47:34,638
<i>in such a horrible death.</i>

1325
01:48:14,472 --> 01:48:17,512
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
Tuesday, December 4, 1934.</i>

1326
01:48:17,540 --> 01:48:19,956
<i>At 5:00 a.m.
we reached Floreana...</i>

1327
01:48:19,978 --> 01:48:23,724
<i>and a signal from Friedo showed that
our approach had been observed.</i>

1328
01:48:23,747 --> 01:48:26,127
<i>Captain Hancock
hurried up the trail...</i>

1329
01:48:26,149 --> 01:48:30,933
<i>and came back with the startling
news that Dr. Ritter is dead.</i>

1330
01:48:30,954 --> 01:48:36,341
<i>Dore considers it an act of providence
that our arrival is so timely.</i>

1331
01:48:36,359 --> 01:48:38,899
<i>When asked about the baroness
and Philippson,</i>

1332
01:48:38,929 --> 01:48:40,932
<i>Dore talks
of hearing screams...</i>

1333
01:48:40,963 --> 01:48:44,003
<i>and alludes to the occurrence
of terrible events,</i>

1334
01:48:44,032 --> 01:48:48,747
<i>but she is too distraught to give
us anything in the way of details.</i>

1335
01:48:48,770 --> 01:48:51,379
<i>Unsatisfied
with Dora's account,</i>

1336
01:48:51,406 --> 01:48:56,359
<i>we proceeded to the Wittmers so we could
hear their version of these happenings.</i>

1337
01:48:56,377 --> 01:48:59,623
<i>We were startled to find
the baroness's tin roof...</i>

1338
01:48:59,647 --> 01:49:03,029
<i>now residing
atop the Wittmefls home.</i>

1339
01:49:03,050 --> 01:49:05,192
<i>The captain queried
Heinz and Margret,</i>

1340
01:49:05,220 --> 01:49:10,698
<i>who maintain that the baroness and
Philippson boarded a yacht to Tahiti.</i>

1341
01:49:10,725 --> 01:49:13,937
<i>I felt as if I were watching
Sherlock Holmes at work,</i>

1342
01:49:13,961 --> 01:49:16,239
<i>but after much relating
and many questions,</i>

1343
01:49:16,263 --> 01:49:19,644
<i>the captain reached
no definitive conclusions.</i>

1344
01:49:23,736 --> 01:49:28,449
<i>[ Reading As Dore] I have decided to
leave Floreana with Captain Hancock.</i>

1345
01:49:28,473 --> 01:49:31,753
<i>I do not know what I will do
back in the world again,</i>

1346
01:49:31,776 --> 01:49:33,816
<i>but go I must.</i>

1347
01:49:33,846 --> 01:49:37,524
<i>I have packed the few
possessions that I treasure,</i>

1348
01:49:37,548 --> 01:49:40,691
<i>carefully gathering
all of Friedrich '5 writings.</i>

1349
01:49:41,719 --> 01:49:44,168
<i>I said good-bye
to Friedrich '5 grave,</i>

1350
01:49:44,189 --> 01:49:48,072
<i>but I did not feel as if
I were leaving him there.</i>

1351
01:49:48,092 --> 01:49:52,134
<i>In some strange way
that I cannot find words for,</i>

1352
01:49:52,162 --> 01:49:56,081
<i>I do not feel
that he is truly dead.</i>

1353
01:49:58,934 --> 01:50:01,645
<i>I have put Friedo under
the charge of the Wittmers...</i>

1354
01:50:01,671 --> 01:50:04,280
<i>as long as they might
stay upon the island.</i>

1355
01:50:04,307 --> 01:50:09,158
<i>They said they would look after
it for me well and truly.</i>

1356
01:50:09,178 --> 01:50:12,424
<i>We and the Wittmers
were never friends,</i>

1357
01:50:12,447 --> 01:50:16,456
<i>but we have been something
more than merely neighbors.</i>

1358
01:50:16,485 --> 01:50:19,559
<i>I wish them well
on Floreana.</i>

1359
01:50:21,656 --> 01:50:24,970
<i>[ Reading As John Garth]
Friday, December 7th, 1934.</i>

1360
01:50:24,993 --> 01:50:28,945
<i>Today</i> we <i>left Floreana
with Dore aboard the Velero.</i>

1361
01:50:28,963 --> 01:50:31,241
<i>Our first stop
was Santa Cruz,</i>

1362
01:50:31,265 --> 01:50:33,977
<i>where we were met
by a German, Kubler,</i>

1363
01:50:34,003 --> 01:50:36,279
<i>and his little girl Carmen.</i>

1364
01:50:37,505 --> 01:50:39,042
[ Carmen ]
I saw her.

1365
01:50:39,072 --> 01:50:41,987
I saw her when
she came on the <i>Velero.</i>

1366
01:50:42,007 --> 01:50:47,360
She went ashore with the Hancocks
and she seemed to be sad.

1367
01:50:47,381 --> 01:50:51,332
She must have been sad, just
suddenly having to leave like that.

1368
01:50:52,552 --> 01:50:54,864
<i>[ Reading As Dore]
My last act on the islands...</i>

1369
01:50:54,887 --> 01:50:56,458
<i>was to meet with
the governor,</i>

1370
01:50:56,488 --> 01:50:58,265
<i>who took my deposition...</i>

1371
01:50:58,290 --> 01:51:01,569
<i>and wrote out a death
certificate for Friedrich.</i>

1372
01:51:01,592 --> 01:51:06,513
<i>In doing so,
a great calm filled my soul.</i>

1373
01:51:07,565 --> 01:51:09,513
<i>I return to the world...</i>

1374
01:51:09,534 --> 01:51:14,352
<i>determined to publish Friedrich's
great philosophical manifesto.</i>

1375
01:51:14,372 --> 01:51:16,217
<i>It was his dearest wish,</i>

1376
01:51:16,241 --> 01:51:19,953
<i>and he was one of
the world's true geniuses.</i>

1377
01:51:19,977 --> 01:51:23,517
<i>He must live on through me.</i>

1378
01:51:26,282 --> 01:51:28,390
<i>[ Reading As Heinz ] The day after
the departure of the Velero,</i>

1379
01:51:28,418 --> 01:51:30,797
<i>we received
a copy of</i> El <i>Universo...</i>

1380
01:51:30,819 --> 01:51:33,735
<i>from a Guayaquil reporter.</i>

1381
01:51:33,756 --> 01:51:36,866
<i>In it is printed an article
written by Dr. Ritter...</i>

1382
01:51:36,893 --> 01:51:38,635
<i>in which the doctor,</i>

1383
01:51:38,660 --> 01:51:41,404
<i>in telling about the disappearance
of the baroness, says...</i>

1384
01:51:41,429 --> 01:51:45,643
<i>that "we," Margret and I,
know all about it.</i>

1385
01:51:45,666 --> 01:51:49,117
<i>Now</i> we <i>know that Dr. Ritter
was trying all along...</i>

1386
01:51:49,137 --> 01:51:51,847
<i>to direct suspicion
towards us.</i>

1387
01:51:51,873 --> 01:51:54,152
<i>We would like to ask
many questions,</i>

1388
01:51:54,175 --> 01:51:58,686
<i>but as Dr. Ritter is dead
he can give no explanation.</i>

1389
01:51:58,714 --> 01:52:01,458
<i>His lips
are sealed forever.</i>

1390
01:52:04,418 --> 01:52:06,024
<i>[ Reading As Margret]
We have transferred...</i>

1391
01:52:06,053 --> 01:52:09,037
<i>all of the valuable things
at Friedo to our place,</i>

1392
01:52:09,056 --> 01:52:12,632
<i>and Friedo now looks
mournful and neglected.</i>

1393
01:52:12,659 --> 01:52:15,768
<i>The upkeep of its garden
is too much for Heinz,</i>

1394
01:52:15,796 --> 01:52:20,306
<i>who is depressed by our recent
experiences with human cussedness.</i>

1395
01:52:20,333 --> 01:52:24,649
<i>Indeed, it is hard for me
to forgive Dr. Ritter.</i>

1396
01:52:24,670 --> 01:52:27,585
<i>There are some things
you cannot forgive--</i>

1397
01:52:27,606 --> 01:52:29,747
<i>not at once anyhow.</i>

1398
01:52:31,643 --> 01:52:34,023
<i>Meanwhile,
the others have all gone...</i>

1399
01:52:34,045 --> 01:52:38,464
<i>and we alone remain on the
entire island of Floreana.</i>

1400
01:52:38,482 --> 01:52:40,657
<i>We do not mind
this solitude,</i>

1401
01:52:40,684 --> 01:52:44,066
<i>for it is the life
we have chosen for ourselves,</i>

1402
01:52:44,087 --> 01:52:47,264
<i>and on the whole
we are well content.</i>

1403
01:52:47,290 --> 01:52:49,431
<i>When we look out
over our land,</i>

1404
01:52:49,459 --> 01:52:52,170
<i>we become filled
with a just pride...</i>

1405
01:52:52,195 --> 01:52:55,736
<i>and can truthfully say we have
accomplished something considerable...</i>

1406
01:52:55,765 --> 01:52:57,805
<i>in two and a half years.</i>

1407
01:52:57,834 --> 01:53:01,444
<i>Already there are two generations
of Wittmers on this island...</i>

1408
01:53:01,471 --> 01:53:03,953
<i>and a flourishing farm.</i>

1409
01:53:03,973 --> 01:53:07,185
<i>We have named our house
Asilo de Ia Paz...</i>

1410
01:53:07,209 --> 01:53:09,749
<i>after a settlement
that was here earlier.</i>

1411
01:53:10,644 --> 01:53:12,719
<i>It seems to be
a fitting name,</i>

1412
01:53:12,748 --> 01:53:16,823
<i>for we have had peace all the
time we have been living there.</i>

1413
01:53:21,055 --> 01:53:22,866
[Tapping]

1414
01:53:27,260 --> 01:53:30,507
[ Carmen ] It's changed very
much because the old people--

1415
01:53:30,532 --> 01:53:32,706
a lot are gone.

1416
01:53:32,732 --> 01:53:35,716
The Divines are gone.

1417
01:53:35,735 --> 01:53:38,183
Andre is gone.

1418
01:53:38,205 --> 01:53:40,153
Karl and my mother
are gone.

1419
01:53:40,174 --> 01:53:42,019
Gus is gone.

1420
01:53:42,042 --> 01:53:44,181
Fritz is gone.

1421
01:53:44,209 --> 01:53:46,818
Just about
from every household...

1422
01:53:46,845 --> 01:53:49,260
at least somebody is gone.

1423
01:53:49,282 --> 01:53:52,027
And, uh, now...

1424
01:53:52,051 --> 01:53:55,330
what were the younger people
are the old folks now.

1425
01:53:55,353 --> 01:53:57,835
I guess Jacqueline and I,
we're the two oldest...

1426
01:53:57,857 --> 01:54:00,635
from the old times still.

1427
01:54:03,494 --> 01:54:06,500
[Jacqueline] I don't say that I
want to go back to that old time...

1428
01:54:06,531 --> 01:54:08,911
because I'm getting older.

1429
01:54:08,933 --> 01:54:13,215
You know?
It was not really an easy life.

1430
01:54:13,237 --> 01:54:14,774
Oh, yeah, yeah.

1431
01:54:14,805 --> 01:54:18,552
And besides that, we never found
what we were dreaming of.

1432
01:54:18,575 --> 01:54:20,579
It was not complete.

1433
01:54:21,845 --> 01:54:26,595
[Gil] Paradise, in this
world, is duly unreal.

1434
01:54:27,883 --> 01:54:30,333
I think the people
are too easygoing.

1435
01:54:30,354 --> 01:54:32,631
They-- They come
and visit the islands.

1436
01:54:32,655 --> 01:54:35,331
They pay their ticket. They come over.
They live on a boat.

1437
01:54:35,357 --> 01:54:39,970
They go to the restaurant. They come and
visit me and they say, "Oh, beautiful."

1438
01:54:39,995 --> 01:54:43,241
They leave and they say,
"You live in a paradise."

1439
01:54:43,265 --> 01:54:45,178
I couldn't agree
any more.

1440
01:54:45,200 --> 01:54:48,115
Unfortunately, it includes myself.
[ Laughs]

1441
01:54:58,011 --> 01:55:00,858
[ Friedel ]
Paradise is not a place.

1442
01:55:00,881 --> 01:55:03,524
It's a condition.

1443
01:55:03,551 --> 01:55:06,090
That's my philosophy.

1444
01:55:06,119 --> 01:55:09,501
And, um, I think that was
one of the things...

1445
01:55:09,522 --> 01:55:12,904
that happened on Galépagos.

1446
01:55:12,925 --> 01:55:15,498
People found out that...

1447
01:55:15,527 --> 01:55:17,908
paradise is not a place.

1448
01:55:24,836 --> 01:55:28,584
[ Fritz] Look, one thing
is very important.

1449
01:55:28,608 --> 01:55:31,054
Wherever you go,

1450
01:55:31,074 --> 01:55:32,988
if you go
out of the society,

1451
01:55:33,011 --> 01:55:34,993
wherever you go...

1452
01:55:36,147 --> 01:55:38,254
you bring you rself.

1453
01:55:38,282 --> 01:55:40,662
And if you are the problem,

1454
01:55:40,685 --> 01:55:42,894
you can go
wherever you want.

1455
01:55:42,920 --> 01:55:44,662
You will have problems.

1456
01:55:44,687 --> 01:55:47,261
Yeah. Because you
are the problems.

1457
01:55:47,290 --> 01:55:50,172
And you take
these problems with you.

1458
01:55:50,193 --> 01:55:51,730
Yeah.
